INSERT INTO `wp_comments` VALUES (1,1,'A WordPress Commenter','wapuu@wordpress.example','https://wordpress.org/','','2024-03-09 11:10:29','2024-03-09 11:10:29','Hi, this is a comment.\nTo get started with moderating, editing, and deleting comments, please visit the Comments screen in the dashboard.\nCommenter avatars come from <a href=\"https://en.gravatar.com/\">Gravatar</a>.',0,'post-trashed','','comment',0,0),(2,73,'Eric Forgette','e4jet@mac.com','http://web.me.com/e4jet/','71.56.184.227','2010-10-06 21:09:22','2010-10-07 02:09:22','Nice work Tom.  That was concise and actually more compelling than other explanations I\'ve seen.\n\nToo bad that last marker you grabbed died right at the end (Murphy\'s Law).\n;-)\n\nAny chance you can link to the video that won?  Just curious...',0,'1','','comment',0,0),(3,73,'fr0gger03','thomas.Twyman@EMC.com','','209.118.159.3','2010-10-07 06:50:43','2010-10-07 11:50:43','Thanks, Eric...  Actually, mine was selected unanimously as the winner.  And i got an iPad out of it!',0,'1','','comment',2,2),(4,73,'Eric Forgette','e4jet@mac.com','http://web.me.com/e4jet/','71.56.184.227','2010-10-09 10:15:26','2010-10-09 15:15:26','Ah, cool.  Congratulations!  I can see why you won.',0,'1','','comment',0,0),(5,90,'Jonas Jansson','jonas.jansson@emc.com','','152.62.109.58','2010-10-06 03:45:56','2010-10-06 08:45:56','Great looking lab, love the geeked out blue lights :)\nI\'m looking into doing something similar, so my question is what did the full environment cost?',0,'1','','comment',0,0),(6,90,'fr0gger03','thomas.Twyman@EMC.com','','209.118.159.3','2010-10-06 06:42:42','2010-10-06 11:42:42','Each server cost about $1200, which is up there for a system i built myself, but i wanted some decent systems I wouldn\'t become frustrated with, at least not soon. ¬†I have built systems before, and you can certainly go cheaper, but for what i wanted I decided to spend a bit more.',0,'1','','comment',5,2),(7,90,'Milo','thomas.milosevic@gmail.com','','72.166.77.101','2011-04-15 00:07:26','2011-04-15 05:07:26','Did you use esx4i? 4.1, 4.0 ...\nI am having trouble getting vmware installed on default system. Couple of differences on system. I have the x6 amd, 790gto video card, 2TB SATA HD. I have read enough articles that I am going to order Intel Pro NIC card. VmWare doesn\'t seem to support onboard NICs. I\'m trying to figure out if there are any custom configs in the BIOS? I\'ve tried several configurations and no luck. Can you explain what you disabled and left enabled in BIOS?\n\nr/Milo',0,'1','','comment',0,0),(8,90,'admin','Tomt@t3websolutions.com','','173.53.119.85','2011-04-23 22:28:52','2011-04-24 03:28:52','I actually didn\'t have to do much...  I left hardware virtualization enabled, turned off all the ports I don\'t need (parallel, serial, etc), and everything worked fine with the exception of the onboard NICs. I have RealTek NICs on my motherboard, and those are explicitly not supported.  ESX (and ESXi) both will usually recognize Intel and Broadcom inboard NICs pretty week, though of course you should check the VMW ompatability guides at http://www.Vmware.com/support.',0,'1','','comment',7,2),(9,103,'Lisa Hammond','lisa.hammond@centrixsoftware.com','http://www.centrixsoftware.com','195.224.113.195','2011-02-03 05:58:55','2011-02-03 10:58:55','Great ideas! \n\nCentrix WorkSpace Universal and iQ products already do this and have thousands of seats in production in global enterprise organizations already!',0,'1','','comment',0,0),(10,112,'Home Lab 3.0 | Tasty Tech','','http://tastytech.t3webinc.com/2011/02/home-lab-3-0/','209.96.240.231','2011-08-22 13:07:53','2011-08-22 18:07:53','[...] there have been some changes to the home lab setup.¬† You may recall, in my post last fall &#8211; Home Lab, Part 2 - I was having some network issues.¬† I enlisted the assistance of one of my local Cisco System [...] ',0,'1','','pingback',0,0),(11,112,'Home Lab v. 4.0 | my occasional IT blog','','http://fr0gger03.wordpress.com/2013/11/25/home-lab-v-4-0/','192.0.80.145','2013-11-25 20:31:57','2013-11-25 20:31:57','[&#8230;] lab setup described in earlier posts (here, here, and here) has actually spent the past year or so in the EMC lab in Columbia, MD, under the care [&#8230;]',0,'1','','pingback',0,0),(12,123,'Technology Short Take #11 - blog.scottlowe.org - The weblog of an IT pro specializing in virtualization, storage, and servers','','http://blog.scottlowe.org/2011/02/17/technology-short-take-11/','74.220.219.129','2011-02-17 18:02:01','2011-02-17 23:02:01','[...] vSpecialist Tom Twyman posted a good write-up on installing PowerPath/VE. It&#8217;s worth reading if you&#8217;re considering PP/VE for your [...] ',0,'1','','pingback',0,0),(13,134,'Home Lab v. 4.0 | my occasional IT blog','','http://fr0gger03.wordpress.com/2013/11/25/home-lab-v-4-0/','192.0.80.145','2013-11-25 20:32:00','2013-11-25 20:32:00','[&#8230;] lab setup described in earlier posts (here, here, and here) has actually spent the past year or so in the EMC lab in Columbia, MD, under the care and feeding [&#8230;]',0,'1','','pingback',0,0),(14,275,'Graphy Goodness&#8230; | my occasional IT blog','','http://fr0gger03.wordpress.com/2013/12/15/graphy-goodness/','192.0.83.170','2013-12-15 14:19:38','2013-12-15 14:19:38','[&#8230;] my previous post, I tried to discuss how the traditional RDBMS, while being very good at storing and tracking [&#8230;]',0,'1','','pingback',0,0),(15,340,'Amrutha','amruthapv2509@gmail.com','','202.3.121.6','2017-09-04 01:04:26','2017-09-04 05:04:26','How to do the same in python . So that I can write a ansible playbook to get the mapping',0,'1','','comment',0,0),(16,340,'Tom','tmvt@mail.com','http://fr0gger03.wordpress.com','108.4.78.20','2017-09-04 10:44:48','2017-09-04 14:44:48','Great question, Amrutha - and I am not sure I am the right person to ask, as I haven\'t really ever done anything in Python.  However, you can check out the following links:\n<a href=\"https://github.com/vmware/pyvmomi\" rel=\"nofollow ugc\">PyVmomi - Python SDK for the VMware vSphere API</a>\n<a href=\"https://github.com/vmware/pyvmomi-community-samples/tree/master/samples\" rel=\"nofollow ugc\">Community Samples for PyVmomi</a>\n\nFinally - if you are interested in vSAN, also be sure to check out our <a href=\"https://blogs.vmware.com/virtualblocks/2016/07/27/vsan-api-cookbook-for-python/\" rel=\"nofollow ugc\">VSAN Management API Cookbook for Python</a> - vSAN specific, of course, but perhaps it will be helpful.\n\nGood luck, Amrutha - please feel free to post additional questions, and please be sure to let me know how you progress!',0,'1','','comment',15,2),(17,340,'Amrutha','amruthapv2509@gmail.com','','202.3.121.6','2017-09-05 01:56:11','2017-09-05 05:56:11','Thanks Tom. I am referring to that library just wanted some help on what data structures to use specifically.',0,'1','','comment',0,0),(18,340,'Amrutha','amruthapv2509@gmail.com','','202.3.121.6','2017-09-12 06:58:44','2017-09-12 10:58:44','Is there any library that I could refer to write PowerCLI scripts for vsphere',0,'1','','comment',0,0),(19,340,'Amrutha','amruthapv2509@gmail.com','','202.3.121.6','2017-09-15 00:26:18','2017-09-15 04:26:18','I started of with PowerShell and the above script was very useful. I wanted to know more about how to get the corresponding lun id, vsserver, volume, aggregate and cluster node(NetApp filer)',0,'1','','comment',0,0),(20,450,'yimeng liu','13619220158@163.com','','208.91.1.34','2017-09-21 09:03:59','2017-09-21 13:03:59','vSAN will automatically reclaim space when a virtual machine is deleted,Is this conclusion refer to vSAN version? I know that vSAN doesn\'t support VAAI because it is built-in Hypervisor, no need to offload. So I think vSAN doesnot have capacity of  VAAI unmap.',0,'1','','comment',0,0),(21,450,'Tom','tmvt@mail.com','http://fr0gger03.wordpress.com','75.146.29.27','2017-09-21 09:26:35','2017-09-21 13:26:35','Correct - UNMAP and TRIM are not yet supported in vSAN... Those are forthcoming.',0,'1','','comment',20,2),(22,450,'yimeng liu','13619220158@163.com','','208.91.1.34','2017-09-22 00:53:48','2017-09-22 04:53:48','Can \'vSAN will automatically reclaim space when a virtual machine is deleted\' be final conclusionÔºüStorage backend of HOL environment may not be real vSAN.',0,'1','','comment',21,0),(23,450,'Tom','tmvt@mail.com','http://fr0gger03.wordpress.com','108.4.78.20','2017-09-22 07:44:32','2017-09-22 11:44:32','Well, in point of fact, vSAN will reclaim space when a virtual machine is deleted.  I should be more clear - TRIM and UNMAP when data is deleted from within the VM are not yet supported, however.   In other words, ad a virtual machine grows, the VMDK grows...  If the virtual machine or the VMDK is deleted, then vSAN will reclaim the space.  If data is deleted from within the virtual machine, however, we do not yet support automatic reclaim of space if the data store is vSAN.  On the other hand, vSphere 6.5 absolutely supports TRIM and UNMAP when data is deleted from within the virtual machine on a FC or iSCSI datastore.\n\nAs for your final comment - ‚ÄúStorage backend of HOL environment may not be real vSAN‚Äù - I‚Äôm not sure what you mean here.',0,'1','','comment',0,2),(24,450,'yimeng liu','13619220158@163.com','','208.91.1.34','2017-09-24 01:16:33','2017-09-24 05:16:33','Thank you. The reply is more clear to understand.',0,'1','','comment',23,0),(25,450,'Ahmed','ahmed_goda@hotmail.com','','212.214.188.126','2018-06-26 15:40:56','2018-06-26 19:40:56','You mentioned \"but if you are looking to reclaim space that has been released within a guest, some extra steps are necessary\" so what is these extra steps that could help to reclaim the space if is is deleted inside the guest OS?',0,'1','','comment',0,0),(26,640,'zmombasaZahir','zmombasa@gmail.com','http://gravatar.com/zmombasa','198.246.222.227','2017-07-12 13:32:54','2017-07-12 17:32:54','Outstanding technical layout of your vSAN cluster and fault domains. \nNow I have a situation whereby customer has 342 hosts. These are going to be built with the latest vSAN 6.6 on ESXi 6.5 latest build and managed by vCenter 6.5 with latest build. How do l even design a fault domain? Each host has 2*400GB SSD and 6 *960 HDD - all flash. Customer wants FTT=2',0,'1','','comment',0,0),(27,640,'Tom','tmvt@mail.com','http://fr0gger03.wordpress.com','173.53.89.17','2017-07-12 23:27:23','2017-07-13 03:27:23','Well, there are few things to keep in mind, of course...  a vSAN datastore is constrained to a single cluster, and of course a vSphere cluster can grow to a maximum of 64 hosts, so you already are into multiple clusters.  The first thing I would decide on is how many clusters, and whether or not you would like to distribute the hosts in each cluster across multiple racks or not.  \n\nFTT=2 may be accomplished with either FTM=RAID1 or RAID6, the difference being in the amount of capacity consumed, as well as overall iops required to support the selected FTM.  \n\nOnce you have decided upon the desired FTM, distribution of hosts across racks, and operational boundaries that may impose limits on cluster size, then you can begin to think about whether you want to use fault domains, how many FD you will need for each cluster, and the number of hosts per FD. ',0,'1','','comment',26,2),(28,640,'tietzjd','joe@tietzinc.com','http://joetietz.wordpress.com','50.75.163.18','2018-01-31 14:24:53','2018-01-31 19:24:53','Well Written your 24 node cross rack, fault domain was what I have in my head for 32 node cluster. Well with one more host :)',0,'1','','comment',0,0),(29,640,'Tom','tmvt@mail.com','http://fr0gger03.wordpress.com','12.31.71.58','2018-02-20 15:51:35','2018-02-20 20:51:35','The VMware Technical Marketing has just incorporated some of this guidance into the official Design and Sizing Guide here - https://storagehub.vmware.com/t/vmware-vsan/vmware-r-vsan-tm-design-and-sizing-guide/fault-domains-9',0,'1','','comment',0,2),(30,640,