-18 22:03:30','2019-08-19 02:03:30','',1000,'http://localhost:8080/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/7-tgw-rt-create.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(1043,2,'2019-08-18 22:03:31','2019-08-19 02:03:31','','8-tgw-rt-create','','inherit','open','closed','','8-tgw-rt-create','','','2019-08-18 22:03:31','2019-08-19 02:03:31','',1000,'http://localhost:8080/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/8-tgw-rt-create.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(1047,2,'2019-08-18 22:08:41','2019-08-19 02:08:41','','9-tgw-rt-create','','inherit','open','closed','','9-tgw-rt-create','','','2019-08-18 22:08:41','2019-08-19 02:08:41','',1000,'http://localhost:8080/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/9-tgw-rt-create.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(1061,2,'2019-08-21 11:21:06','2019-08-21 15:21:06','<!-- wp:image {\"align\":\"left\",\"id\":1062} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image alignleft\"><img src=\"http://localhost:8080/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/3a7a46231.jpg?w=191\" alt=\"3A7A4623(1)\" class=\"wp-image-1062\" /></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><span style=\"text-decoration:underline\"><strong>Tom Twyman</strong></span></h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>I have been in technology for my entire career.¬† After graduating from a tiny school with a degree in music (officially a singer by training and education), I quickly found my way into technology as a corporate trainer for New Horizons.¬† I spent several years as a Microsoft Certified Trainer, then a Citrix Certified Instructor, with all the certifications along the way.¬† After several years I joined a small consultancy and reseller helping customers deploy Winframe, Metaframe, Presentation Server and then XenApp.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Along the way I learned about VMware, and in doing so found a company and a technology I love.&nbsp; I have been with VMware since 2007 (though I did spend a short hiatus as a vSpecialist with EMC), in a variety of roles, including Systems Engineer for our core products, Solutions Architect for professional services, vSAN Systems Engineer and now VMware Cloud on AWS Systems Engineer.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><a href=\"https://www.linkedin.com/in/tomtwyman/\">https://www.linkedin.com/in/tomtwyman/</a></li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->','About','','publish','closed','closed','','about','','','2019-08-21 11:21:06','2019-08-21 15:21:06','',0,'http://occasional-it.com/?page_id=1061',0,'page','',0),(1062,2,'2019-08-21 11:04:44','2019-08-21 15:04:44','','3A7A4623(1)','','inherit','open','closed','','3a7a46231','','','2019-08-21 11:04:44','2019-08-21 15:04:44','',1061,'http://localhost:8080/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/3a7a46231.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(1078,2,'2019-05-22 09:31:09','2019-05-22 13:31:09','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>It was VMworld 2008, and if I remember correctly it was Raghu Raghuram that stated, \"If we run out of hard problems to solve, then we go out of business.\" With the developments I have seen over the past year, I am more convinced than ever that not only are we solving hard problems for our customers, we continue to do things only VMware is capable of doing.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:more -->\n<!--more-->\n<!-- /wp:more -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>There is a LOT going on right now... unbelievably, we continue to enhance our core platform (more on this in a minute), we are acquiring companies and technologies at a fairly rapid clip, we are growing our presence in the cloud through strategic partnerships and we continue to expand our capabilities across our portfolio <em>well beyond</em> basic virtualization. Furthermore, we are doing so in a fashion that enables our customers to accelerate their adoption of cloud - no matter whose cloud it is - through intelligent integration and use of technology. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":1080,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"http://localhost:8080/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/vmw-strategy.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-1080\" /></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Some version of the above graphic may be seen in nearly every presentation delivered by a VMware employee...  I propose to give you my own interpretation of the above...  When I look at everything we are doing, everything that we have going on, and try to boil it down, I come up with basically 4 things...</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>1 - Common Infrastructure and Operations</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>It is hard to avoid this as the basis for everything we are doing.  By spreading the deliciousness of vSphere across as many environments as possible, we can allow our customers to leverage their well established set of operational procedures for vSphere across multiple cloud environments - extending their investment in both people and technology.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>We are already doing this with our global network of cloud providers (<a href=\"https://www.vmware.com/partners/service-provider.html\">https://www.vmware.com/partners/service-provider.html</a>) - We have literally thousands of partners signed up into this program.  Right off the bat, this gives our customers ample choice and flexibility for where to place their infrastructure.  Furthermore, we are now a few years into our relationship with Amazon Web Services - VMware Cloud on AWS is growing quickly, providing tight integration with AWS native services and unprecedented flexibility.  Recently we announced Azure VMware Solutions and Google Cloud VMware Solutions - currently both sold and supported through partners - to provide customers looking for tight integration with Azure or GCP a similar experience to VMC on AWS.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":1082,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"http://localhost:8080/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/peanutbutter.jpg\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-1082\" /></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>VMware vSphere is basically the peanut butter of cloud.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>2 - VMware-Enhanced Cloud Native Technologies</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong><em>Where it makes sense</em></strong>, we are looking to enhance native cloud functionality through intelligent application of VMware intellectual property.  Just like peanut butter, we see our technology getting sticky in the cloud.  Just to point out three such efforts:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li>NSX Cloud (<a href=\"https://www.vmware.com/products/nsx-cloud.html\">https://www.vmware.com/products/nsx-cloud.html</a>) - providing microsegmentation across Azure and AWS.</li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li>Enterprise PKS (<a href=\"https://cloud.vmware.com/vmware-enterprise-pks\">https://cloud.vmware.com/vmware-enterprise-pks</a>) - providing an enterprise-ready implementation of Kubernetes for vSphere, GCP, AWS and Azure.</li><li>Cloud Foundation for EC2 - (<a href=\"https://cloud.vmware.com/community/2018/11/29/vmware-cloud-foundation-ec2-overview/\">https://cloud.vmware.com/community/2018/11/29/vmware-cloud-foundation-ec2-overview/</a>) - announced last year at VMworld, this is a project we are working on to enhance the experience of those customers interested in AWS Outposts, especially if running both VMC as well as EC2 on Outpost.</li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>There are more, of course...</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Our customers are actively investigation all kinds of cloud-native technologies, and frequently run into gaps in functionality, lack of enterprise readiness, or operational differences that delay or scuttle their projects altogether.  We (VMware) have the ability to extend our robust enterprise functionality (such as microsegmentation) across multiple disparate infrastructures, allowing our customers to accelerate their adoption of cloud-native technologies in an enterprise environment.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>3 - Cloud-Native Enhanced VMware Technologies</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"align\":\"left\",\"id\":1083,\"width\":172,\"height\":229,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\"} -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-image\"><figure class=\"alignleft size-large is-resized\"><img src=\"http://localhost:8080/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/jelly.jpg\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-1083\" width=\"172\" height=\"229\" /></figure></div>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>I see this as an extension of our \"Common Infrastructure and Operations\" strategy - but I think of this as the jelly in the sandwich.  Customers all around the world are developing expertise in the cloud-native provider of their choice, but still finding value in their vSphere environment as well. Therefore, we see it as in everyone\'s best interest to allow our customers to not only be able to extend their VMware expertise into the cloud provider of their choice, but also to extend the cloud-native technologies of their choice into native VMware environments.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>I am thinking here about things like:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li><strong><u>AWS Greengrass</u></strong>, which extends AWS to edge devices so they can act locally on the data they generate, while still using the cloud for management, analytics, and durable storage.  AWS Greengrass is already available as a  vSphere OVA for deployment to a vSphere edge environment.</li><li><strong><u>AWS Relational Database Services</u></strong> - announced last year, Amazon and VMware are working together to allow our joint customers to extend their AWS RDS infrastructure on-prem to vSphere environments.</li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>4 - Cross Cloud Governance and Visibility</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Where it makes sense, provide cloud management and governance across any/all environments for transparency of decisions.  We have been on a journey over the past few years to provide a multitude of tools to allow our customers to be able to make decisions on where to deploy their workloads, as well as to be able to secure, monitor, track and troubleshoot those deployments over time.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li>Cloud Automation Services</li><li>Log Intelligence</li><li>Network Insight</li><li>Cloud Health</li><li>WaveFront</li><li>Et cetera...</li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>This portfolio will continue to grow over time into a comprehensive governance platform for a multi-cloud environment.  Like a couple pieces of savory sourdough bread, our customers need something they can use to help wrap their heads and hands around their infrastructure and applications as their IT landscape becomes more and more distributed.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"align\":\"right\",\"id\":1084,\"width\":244,\"height\":136,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\"} -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-image\"><figure class=\"alignright size-large is-resized\"><img src=\"http://localhost:8080/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/pbj.jpg\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-1084\" width=\"244\" height=\"136\" /></figure></div>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>As VMware continues to grow, I see our influence growing as well.   Just as years ago virtualization fundamentally changed how infrastructure is engineered and built, I see  the cloud landscape undergoing similar changes.  I don\'t know yet if VMware will achieve its place as a true governance platform between multiple cloud providers, but we are better positioned to do so than anyone else, and we are off to a great start!</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','The Best Peanut Butter &amp; Jelly Sandwich for the Cloud','','publish','open','open','','the-best-peanut-butter-jelly-sandwich-for-the-cloud','','','2019-05-22 09:31:09','2019-05-22 13:31:09','',0,'http://occasional-it.com/?p=1078',0,'post','',0),(1080,2,'2019-08-22 14:58:40','2019-08-22 18:58:40','','vmw-strategy','','inherit','open','closed','','vmw-strategy','','','2019-08-22 14:58:40','2019-08-22 18:58:40','',0,'http://localhost:8080/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/vmw-strategy.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(1082,2,'2019-08-22 15:07:21','2019-08-22 19:07:21','','peanutbutter','','inherit','open','closed','','peanutbutter','','','2019-08-22 15:07:21','2019-08-22 19:07:21','',0,'http://localhost:8080/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/peanutbutter.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(1083,2,'2019-08-22 15:07:34','2019-08-22 19:07:34','','jelly','','inherit','open','closed','','jelly','','','2019-08-22 15:07:34','2019-08-22 19:07:34','',0,'http://localhost:8080/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/jelly.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(1084,2,'2019-08-22 15:07:43','2019-08-22 19:07:43','','pbj','Peanut butter and raspberry jelly sandwich on wooden background. Perfect sweet breakfast. Close up.; Shutterstock ID 348863390','inherit','open','closed','','pbj','','','2019-08-22 15:07:43','2019-08-22 19:07:43','',0,'http://localhost:8080/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/pbj.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(1088,2,'2019-09-03 16:40:00','2019-09-03 20:40:00','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In <a href=\"https://occasional-it.com/2019/08/31/default-route-in-vmc-on-aws-part-1/\">Part 1</a> and <a href=\"https://occasional-it.com/2019/09/03/default-route-in-vmc-on-aws-part-2/\">Part 2 </a>of this series, I discussed the theory behind how one might influence the default route in VMC on AWS, particularly when used with an AWS Transit Gateway.  In the final post for this series, I will walk through the steps necessary to successfully advertise the default route from an attached VPC through a Transit Gateway.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:more -->\n<!--more-->\n<!-- /wp:more -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>For the purposes of this article, I will return to the following, relatively simple architecture:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":1209,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"http://localhost:8080/wp-content/uploads/2019/09/2-1a-desired-state.png?w=840\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-1209\" /></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In the diagram, we are looking to place a pair of load-balanced firewalls in the \"Security VPC\" - which also means the default route (0.0.0.0/0) for the entire environment must point to the EC2 firewall instances in that VPC.  For us to achieve this result, we must achieve a routing infrastructure as follows:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":1210,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"http://localhost:8080/wp-content/uploads/2019/09/2-2a-desired-routing.png?w=840\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-1210\" /></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>As we see in the screen shots below, I have a Software Defined Datacenter in VMC on AWS:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:jetpack/tiled-gallery {\"className\":\"is-style-columns\",\"columnWidths\":[[24.627631019262914,75.3723689807371]],\"ids\":[1105,1106]} -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-jetpack-tiled-gallery aligncenter is-style-columns\"><div class=\"tiled-gallery__gallery\"><div class=\"tiled-gallery__row\"><div class=\"tiled-gallery__col\" style=\"flex-basis:24.627631019263%;\"><figure class=\"tiled-gallery__item\"><img alt=\"\" data-height=\"735\" data-id=\"1105\" data-link=\"https://occasional-it.com/1-sddc-overview-1/\" data-url=\"http://localhost:8080/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/1-sddc-overview-1.png\" data-width=\"604\" src=\"http://localhost:8080/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/1-sddc-overview-1.png\" /></figure></div><div class=\"tiled-gallery__col\" style=\"flex-basis:75.372368980737%;\"><figure class=\"tiled-gallery__item\"><img alt=\"\" data-height=\"692\" data-id=\"1106\" data-link=\"https://occasional-it.com/2-sddc-connected-vpc/\" data-url=\"http://localhost:8080/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/2-sddc-connected-vpc.png\" data-width=\"1751\" src=\"http://localhost:8080/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/2-sddc-connected-vpc.png\" /></figure></div></div></div></div>\n<!-- /wp:jetpack/tiled-gallery -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>You can see that the SDDC has a management CIDR of 10.125.0.0/16, and (not shown) a single compute segment of 192.168.1.0/24. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Leveraging the most excellent <a rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" aria-label=\"PowerCLI modules for VMC and NSX-T from William Lam\'s blog (opens in a new tab)\" href=\"https://www.virtuallyghetto.com/2018/09/getting-started-with-the-new-nsx-t-policy-api-in-vmc.html\" target=\"_blank\">PowerCLI modules for VMC and NSX-T from William Lam\'s blog</a>, we can quickly and easily pull the routing table from the SDDC, as shown below:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:coblocks/gallery-stacked {\"gutter\":5,\"radius\":5,\"captions\":true} -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-coblocks-gallery-stacked alignfull\"><ul class=\"coblocks-gallery has-border-radius-5 has-fullwidth-images has-margin\"><li class=\"coblocks-gallery--item\"><figure class=\"coblocks-gallery--figure has-margin-bottom-5\"><img src=\"http://localhost:8080/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/14-powercli-connect.png?w=840\" alt=\"\" data-id=\"1118\" data-link=\"http://occasional-it.com/14-powercli-connect/\" class=\"wp-image-1118 has-shadow-none\" /><figcaption class=\"coblocks-gallery--caption\">Connecting to VMC...</figcaption></figure></li><li class=\"coblocks-gallery--item\"><figure class=\"coblocks-gallery--figure has-margin-bottom-5\"><img src=\"http://localhost:8080/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/15-powercli-rt-before-1.png\" alt=\"\" data-id=\"1132\" data-link=\"https://occasional-it.com/15-powercli-rt-before-1/\" class=\"wp-image-1132 has-shadow-none\" /></figure></li></ul></div>\n<!-- /wp:coblocks/gallery-stacked -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>While there are clearly a number of networks the routing table has entries for, I have circled in red those for the management CIDR (10.125.0.0/16), the linked VPC (172.32.0.0/16), and the <strong>default route (0.0.0.0/0).</strong>  You can clearly see the default route pointing to an address local to the management CIDR - notice also the administrative distance has been set artificially high, which will allow it to be overridden.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>I have also built out a native VPC in AWS, using the 172.31.0.0/16 CIDR, along with subnets for each availability zone:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:coblocks/gallery-masonry {\"align\":\"wide\",\"gridSize\":\"lrg\"} -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-coblocks-gallery-masonry alignwide\"><div class=\"coblocks-gallery has-caption-style-dark has-gutter\"><ul class=\"has-grid-lrg has-gutter-15 has-gutter-mobile-15\"><li class=\"coblocks-gallery--item\"><figure class=\"coblocks-gallery--figure\"><img src=\"http://localhost:8080/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/screen-shot-2019-08-26-at-2.24.42-pm-1.png?w=840\" alt=\"\" data-id=\"1091\" class=\"wp-image-1091\" /></figure></li><li class=\"coblocks-gallery--item\"><figure class=\"coblocks-gallery--figure\"><img src=\"http://localhost:8080/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/screen-shot-2019-08-26-at-2.24.53-pm.png?w=840\" alt=\"\" data-id=\"1092\" class=\"wp-image-1092\" /></figure></li><li class=\"coblocks-gallery--item\"><figure class=\"coblocks-gallery--figure\"><img src=\"http://localhost:8080/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/screen-shot-2019-08-26-at-2.25.11-pm.png?w=840\" alt=\"\" data-id=\"1093\" class=\"wp-image-1093\" /></figure></li><li class=\"coblocks-gallery--item\"><figure class=\"coblocks-gallery--figure\"><img src=\"http://localhost:8080/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/screen-shot-2019-08-26-at-2.25.30-pm.png?w=840\" alt=\"\" data-id=\"1094\" class=\"wp-image-1094\" /></figure></li></ul></div></div>\n<!-- /wp:coblocks/gallery-masonry -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>As you can see, the route table for the VPC contains only the 172.31.0.0/16 CIDR.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In order to achieve the routing result depicted at the beginning of this post, we must complete the following.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3>1- Create a Transit Gateway</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>As you can see below, I have created a transit gateway - as nothing is attached to the gateway yet, the route table for the TGW is empty.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:gallery {\"ids\":[1108,1109],\"linkTo\":\"none\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-gallery columns-2 is-cropped\"><ul class=\"blocks-gallery-grid\"><li class=\"blocks-gallery-item\"><figure><img src=\"http://localhost:8080/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/5-tgw.png?w=1024\" data-id=\"1108\" data-link=\"https://occasional-it.com/5-tgw/\" class=\"wp-image-1108\" /></figure></li><li class=\"blocks-gallery-item\"><figure><img src=\"http://localhost:8080/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/6-tgw-rt-before.png?w=1024\" data-id=\"1109\" data-link=\"https://occasional-it.com/6-tgw-rt-before/\" class=\"wp-image-1109\" /></figure></li></ul></figure>\n<!-- /wp:gallery -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3>2- Create the VPC Attachment</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In the images below, you can see I have created the VPC attachment to the TGW for my native AWS VPC.  Once the attachment is complete, the Transit Gateway Route Table immediately populates with the networks from the attached VPC.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:gallery {\"ids\":[1110,1111],\"linkTo\":\"none\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-gallery columns-2 is-cropped\"><ul class=\"blocks-gallery-grid\"><li class=\"blocks-gallery-item\"><figure><img src=\"http://localhost:8080/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/7-tgw-vpc-attach.png?w=1024\" data-id=\"1110\" data-link=\"https://occasional-it.com/7-tgw-vpc-attach/\" class=\"wp-image-1110\" /></figure></li><li class=\"blocks-gallery-item\"><figure><img src=\"http://localhost:8080/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/8-tgw-rt-vpc.png?w=1024\" data-id=\"1111\" data-link=\"https://occasional-it.com/8-tgw-rt-vpc/\" class=\"wp-image-1111\" /></figure></li></ul></figure>\n<!-- /wp:gallery -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3>3- Create the VPN Attachment for the Transit Gateway</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>As you may already know, today only a VPN attachment is supported from VMC on AWS to a Transit Gateway.  In the images below, you can see the VPN has been created, and the Transit Gateway Route Table has automatically updated to include the SDDC networks. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:coblocks/gallery-stacked {\"captions\":true} -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-coblocks-gallery-stacked alignfull\"><ul class=\"coblocks-gallery has-fullwidth-images\"><li class=\"coblocks-gallery--item\"><figure class=\"coblocks-gallery--figure\"><img src=\"http://localhost:8080/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/9-tgw-attach-vpn.png?w=840\" alt=\"\" data-id=\"1112\" data-link=\"http://occasional-it.com/9-tgw-attach-vpn/\" class=\"wp-image-1112 has-shadow-none\" /><figcaption class=\"coblocks-gallery--caption\">TGW VPN Attachment</figcaption></figure></li><li class=\"coblocks-gallery--item\"><figure class=\"coblocks-gallery--figure\"><img src=\"http://localhost:8080/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/10-tgw-attach-vpn.png?w=840\" alt=\"\" data-id=\"1113\" data-link=\"http://occasional-it.com/10-tgw-attach-vpn/\" class=\"wp-image-1113 has-shadow-none\" /><figcaption class=\"coblocks-gallery--caption\">TGW VPN Attachment Details - 1</figcaption></figure></li><li class=\"coblocks-gallery--item\"><figure class=\"coblocks-gallery--figure\"><img src=\"http://localhost:8080/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/11-tgw-attach-vpn.png?w=840\" alt=\"\" data-id=\"1114\" data-link=\"http://occasional-it.com/11-tgw-attach-vpn/\" class=\"wp-image-1114 has-shadow-none\" /><figcaption class=\"coblocks-gallery--caption\">TGW VPN Attachment Details - 2</figcaption></figure></li><li class=\"coblocks-gallery--item\"><figure class=\"coblocks-gallery--figure\"><img src=\"http://localhost:8080/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/12-sddc-vpn.png?w=840\" alt=\"\" data-id=\"1115\" data-link=\"http://occasional-it.com/12-sddc-vpn/\" class=\"wp-image-1115 has-shadow-none\" /><figcaption class=\"coblocks-gallery--caption\">SDDC VPN</figcaption></figure></li><li class=\"coblocks-gallery--item\"><figure class=\"coblocks-gallery--figure\"><img src=\"http://localhost:8080/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/13-tgw-rt-penult.png?w=840\" alt=\"\" data-id=\"1116\" data-link=\"http://occasional-it.com/13-tgw-rt-penult/\" class=\"wp-image-1116 has-shadow-none\" /><figcaption class=\"coblocks-gallery--caption\">Updated Transit Gateway Route Table</figcaption></figure></li></ul></div>\n<!-- /wp:coblocks/gallery-stacked -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3>4- Inject the Default Route</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>This is the most important part of the exercise - we have to inject the default route into the Transit Gateway Route Table to be sure other entities (like our SDDC) receive the propagated route from the TGW.  </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":1211,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"http://localhost:8080/wp-content/uploads/2019/09/2-3a-desired-routing-insert-here.png?w=840\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-1211\" /></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Simply navigate to the TGW Route table, go to the \"Routes\" tab, and click Create Route.  Enter a network of \"0.0.0.0/0\" and select the <em>Transit Gateway attachment for the native AWS VPC</em> - in our example it is the attachment labeled with \"VPC\" rather than \"VPN.\"  The image below shows the end result of the Transit Gateway Route Table.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":1121,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"http://localhost:8080/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/16-tgw-rt-static.png?w=1024\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-1121\" /></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3>5- Verify Your Changes</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Once the default route has been successfully injected into the Transit Gateway Route Table, it will automatically propagate to your SDDC.  We can confirm this in the UI, as well as through PowerCLI.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:coblocks/gallery-stacked {\"captions\":true} -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-coblocks-gallery-stacked alignfull\"><ul class=\"coblocks-gallery has-fullwidth-images\"><li class=\"coblocks-gallery--item\"><figure class=\"coblocks-gallery--figure\"><img src=\"http://localhost:8080/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/screen-shot-2019-08-26-at-10.10.38-pm.png?w=840\" alt=\"\" data-id=\"1141\" data-link=\"http://occasional-it.com/?attachment_id=1141\" class=\"wp-image-1141 has-shadow-none\" /><figcaption class=\"coblocks-gallery--caption\">SDDC VPN - Show Routes</figcaption></figure></li><li class=\"coblocks-gallery--item\"><figure class=\"coblocks-gallery--figure\"><img src=\"http://localhost:8080/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/screen-shot-2019-08-26-at-10.11.00-pm.png?w=840\" alt=\"\" data-id=\"1142\" data-link=\"http://occasional-it.com/?attachment_id=1142\" class=\"wp-image-1142 has-shadow-none\" /><figcaption class=\"coblocks-gallery--caption\">SDDC VPN - Learned Routes</figcaption></figure></li><li class=\"coblocks-gallery--item\"><figure class=\"coblocks-gallery--figure\"><img src=\"http://localhost:8080/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/18-sddc-learned-q0-powercli-a.png\" alt=\"\" data-id=\"1123\" data-link=\"http://occasional-it.com/18-sddc-learned-q0-powercli-a/\" class=\"wp-image-1123 has-shadow-none\" /><figcaption class=\"coblocks-gallery--caption\">PowerCLI - SDDC Route Table</figcaption></figure></li><li class=\"coblocks-gallery--item\"><figure class=\"coblocks-gallery--figure\"><img src=\"http://localhost:8080/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/19-sddc-learned-q0-powercli-b.png\" alt=\"\" data-id=\"1124\" data-link=\"http://occasional-it.com/19-sddc-learned-q0-powercli-b/\" class=\"wp-image-1124 has-shadow-none\" /><figcaption class=\"coblocks-gallery--caption\">PowerCLI - SDDC Routes, BGP Only</figcaption></figure></li></ul></div>\n<!-- /wp:coblocks/gallery-stacked -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>That\'s all there is to it - you can clearly see the default route is directed to the BGP addresses for the VPN, leading to the Transit Gateway.  </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Default Route in VMC on AWS - Part 3','','publish','open','open','','default-route-in-vmc-on-aws-part-3','','','2019-09-03 16:40:00','2019-09-03 20:40:00','',0,'http://occasional-it.com/?p=1088',0,'post','',2),(1091,2,'2019-08-26 19:09:52','2019-08-26 23:09:52','','Screen Shot 2019-08-26 at 2.24.42 PM','','inherit','open','closed','','screen-shot-2019-08-26-at-2-24-42-pm','','','2019-08-26 19:09:52','2019-08-26 23:09:52','',1088,'http://localhost:8080/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/screen-shot-2019-08-26-at-2.24.42-pm-1.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(1092,2,'2019-08-26 19:09:54','2019-08-26 23:09:54','','Screen Shot 2019-08-26 at 2.24.53 PM','','inherit','open','closed','','screen-shot-2019-08-26-at-2-24-53-pm','','','2019-08-26 19:09:54','2019-08-26 23:09:54','',1088,'http://localhost:8080/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/screen-shot-2019-08-26-at-2.24.53-pm.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(1093,2,'2019-08-26 19:09:55','2019-08-26 23:09:55','','Screen Shot 2019-08-26 at 2.25.11 PM','','inherit','open','