,'http://localhost:8080/wp-content/uploads/2020/04/lo-1-initial-summary-1.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(1329,2,'2020-05-20 13:15:44','2020-05-20 17:15:44','','mohawk-squawk-2-logo-sm','','inherit','open','closed','','mohawk-squawk-2-logo-sm','','','2020-05-20 13:15:44','2020-05-20 17:15:44','',0,'http://localhost:8080/wp-content/uploads/2020/05/mohawk-squawk-2-logo-sm.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(1330,2,'2020-05-20 13:15:46','2020-05-20 17:15:46','','mohawk-squawk-logo-sm','','inherit','open','closed','','mohawk-squawk-logo-sm','','','2020-05-20 13:15:46','2020-05-20 17:15:46','',0,'http://localhost:8080/wp-content/uploads/2020/05/mohawk-squawk-logo-sm.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(1331,2,'2020-05-20 13:15:48','2020-05-20 17:15:48','','punk-rock-squawk-logo-sm','','inherit','open','closed','','punk-rock-squawk-logo-sm','','','2020-05-20 13:15:48','2020-05-20 17:15:48','',0,'http://localhost:8080/wp-content/uploads/2020/05/punk-rock-squawk-logo-sm.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(1332,2,'2020-05-20 13:15:49','2020-05-20 17:15:49','','squawk-closeup-logo-sm','','inherit','open','closed','','squawk-closeup-logo-sm','','','2020-05-20 13:15:49','2020-05-20 17:15:49','',0,'http://localhost:8080/wp-content/uploads/2020/05/squawk-closeup-logo-sm.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(1333,2,'2020-05-20 13:15:51','2020-05-20 17:15:51','','squawk-front-logo-sm','','inherit','open','closed','','squawk-front-logo-sm','','','2020-05-20 13:15:51','2020-05-20 17:15:51','',0,'http://localhost:8080/wp-content/uploads/2020/05/squawk-front-logo-sm.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(1334,2,'2020-05-20 13:15:53','2020-05-20 17:15:53','','squawk-profile-logo-sm','','inherit','open','closed','','squawk-profile-logo-sm','','','2020-05-20 13:15:53','2020-05-20 17:15:53','',0,'http://localhost:8080/wp-content/uploads/2020/05/squawk-profile-logo-sm.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(1335,2,'2020-05-20 13:20:02','2020-05-20 17:20:02','','img_0944','','inherit','open','closed','','img_0944','','','2020-05-20 13:20:02','2020-05-20 17:20:02','',0,'http://localhost:8080/wp-content/uploads/2020/05/img_0944.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(1336,2,'2020-05-20 13:20:07','2020-05-20 17:20:07','','img_0940','','inherit','open','closed','','img_0940','','','2020-05-20 13:20:07','2020-05-20 17:20:07','',0,'http://localhost:8080/wp-content/uploads/2020/05/img_0940.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(1337,2,'2020-05-20 13:20:11','2020-05-20 17:20:11','','img_0721','','inherit','open','closed','','img_0721','','','2020-05-20 13:20:11','2020-05-20 17:20:11','',0,'http://localhost:8080/wp-content/uploads/2020/05/img_0721.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(1338,2,'2020-05-20 13:20:15','2020-05-20 17:20:15','','20170928_143049654_ios','','inherit','open','closed','','20170928_143049654_ios','','','2020-05-20 13:20:15','2020-05-20 17:20:15','',0,'http://localhost:8080/wp-content/uploads/2020/05/20170928_143049654_ios.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(1339,2,'2020-05-20 13:25:17','2020-05-20 17:25:17','','img_0324','','inherit','open','closed','','img_0324','','','2020-05-20 13:25:17','2020-05-20 17:25:17','',0,'http://localhost:8080/wp-content/uploads/2020/05/img_0324.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(1340,2,'2020-06-01 11:13:36','2020-06-01 15:13:36','<!-- wp:image {\"className\":\"size-large\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"https://i0.wp.com/nicovmc.files.wordpress.com/2020/05/screenshot-2020-05-29-at-14.37.26.png?quality=80&amp;w=1125&amp;ssl=1\" alt=\"\" /></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:quote -->\n<blockquote class=\"wp-block-quote\"><p>Since I released PyVMC (a Python-based client to manage VMware Cloud on AWS co-created with Matt Dreyer) on my blog and as a VMware Fling, I‚Äôve seen ‚Ä¶</p><cite><a href=\"http://nicovibert.com/2020/06/01/fling-update-pyvmc-1-1-release-and-a-walkthrough-through-some-python-code/\">Fling Update: PyVMC 1.1 release (and a walkthrough through some Python code)</a></cite></blockquote>\n<!-- /wp:quote -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Great update to PyVMC from Nico- thanks Nico!</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Fling Update: PyVMC 1.1 release (and a walkthrough through some Python code)','','publish','open','open','','fling-update-pyvmc-1-1-release-and-a-walkthrough-through-some-python-code','','','2020-06-01 11:13:36','2020-06-01 15:13:36','',0,'http://occasional-it.com/2020/06/01/fling-update-pyvmc-1-1-release-and-a-walkthrough-through-some-python-code/',0,'post','',0),(1344,2,'2020-09-21 16:23:24','2020-09-21 20:23:24','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>My goal with this post is not to unpack all the technical detail behind any of these technologies, but rather to demonstrate the convergence of three in-demand features from VMare and AWS - HCX, Direct Connect, and Transit Gateway.  This convergence represents years of extended effort on the part of both VMware and AWS, as well as no small number of Solution Architects, Product Managers, software engineers, and customers.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:more -->\n<!--more-->\n<!-- /wp:more -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>Background</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Since we first announced VMware Cloud on AWS, one of our secret weapons (#notsosecret) has been Hybrid Cloud Extension (HCX).  The ability to enable cross-vCenter / cross-cloud migrations of virtual machines <em>without also requiring massive changes to your existing infrastructure</em> is incredibly compelling.  Here is one of my favorite blogs on the topic:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li><a rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" href=\"https://www.virtuallyghetto.com/2017/12/getting-started-with-hybrid-cloud-extension-hcx-on-vmware-cloud-on-aws.html\" target=\"_blank\">Getting Started with HCX and VMC on AWS</a></li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>It would be a major oversight if I did not also mention this most excellent demo from my good friend Sean Lambert (@vSeanLambert, #cloudTAM) showing HCX used to migrate between two SDDCs in VMC on AWS:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li><a rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" href=\"https://street2clouds.wordpress.com/2020/05/29/sddc-to-sddc-hcx-migrations-c2c-migrations-demo/\" target=\"_blank\">https://street2clouds.wordpress.com/2020/05/29/sddc-to-sddc-hcx-migrations-c2c-migrations-demo/</a></li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>And as you might expect, lots of customers have wanted to run their HCX migrations over Direct Connect (DX).  We have made this relatively simple by providing a network profile for HCX to use in  VMC on AWS that integrates directly with a customer\'s DX.  Others have written about both using AWS DX with VMC on AWS:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li><a href=\"https://nicovibert.com/2019/03/18/aws-direct-connect-deep-dive-and-integration-with-vmware-cloud-on-aws/\">https://nicovibert.com/2019/03/18/aws-direct-connect-deep-dive-and-integration-with-vmware-cloud-on-aws/</a></li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>Enter AWS Transit Gateway</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Nearly as soon as Amazon announced their Transit Gateway in late 2018, customers and vendors alike were trying to figure out how to integrate with it, and VMware customers were no exception.  There is a ton of interest in the integration between VMware Cloud on AWS and Transit Gateway - for the simple reason that it simplifies the routing architecture to the cloud, as well as the day-to-day administration of routes.  There has been plenty written on TGW and VMC already, and I do not plan to re-hash it here... I will once again simply provide the references for you to investigate:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li><a href=\"http://www.gilles.cloud/2018/12/aws-transit-gateway-and-vmware-cloud-on.html\">http://www.gilles.cloud/2018/12/aws-transit-gateway-and-vmware-cloud-on.html </a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.gilles.cloud/2019/12/aws-transitive-routing-with-transit.html\">http://www.gilles.cloud/2019/12/aws-transitive-routing-with-transit.html </a></li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>There are unfortunately some limitations with a \'native\' AWS TGW and VMware Cloud on AWS - most significantly the fact that a VMC SDDC may not attach to a TGW using a \'native\' VPC attachment.  The SDDC may only attach using a VPN attachment, which limits it to 1.25 Gbps throughput, which may severely limit the network performance from the SDDC over the TGW.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>Introducing VMware Transit Connect</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Since Transit Connect is essentially a VMware-managed Transit Gateway and allows attaching at native speeds, it eliminates this throughput issue, as well as some of the more subtle support issues that may arise by trying to perform vMotion tasks over a 3-rd party routing infrastructure.  My colleague Gilles Chekroun (@twgilles) put together a fantastic overview of everything you need to know about the VMware Transit Connect.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li><a href=\"https://youtu.be/QVe9SPQn4cA\">https://youtu.be/QVe9SPQn4cA</a></li><li><a rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" href=\"http://www.gilles.cloud/2020/06/vmware-cloud-on-aws-managed-transit.html\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.gilles.cloud/2020/06/vmware-cloud-on-aws-managed-transit.html</a></li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Beginning today, Transit Connect is now available with VMware Cloud on AWS SDDC version 1.12.  This first became available in VMware Cloud on AWS with SDDC version 1.11 - though to gain this functionality it had to be enabled by request.  Now that SDDC version 1.12 is generally available, all new customers will be enabled with the ability to deploy a Transit Connect (existing customers may have to wait until their org / SDDC is upgraded).</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>I had the opportunity recently to run a proof of concept for a customer, and as it turns out their preferred / optimal path to the cloud leverages a Direct Connect (with DX Gateway) - so even though one of the primary use cases for Transit Connect is to enable high-throughput communications between multiple SDDCs, in this case it simply served to enable the customer to further utilize their existing fiber connection to AWS.  This customer wanted to be able to migrate workloads over to VMC on AWS using HCX to maintain their existing IP space.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>Configuring HCX with VTC</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>We started by creating a couple compute segments in the SDDC - this was to ensure we could validate the advertisements of cloud-based networks back over the Transit Connect and DX.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":1349,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"http://localhost:8080/wp-content/uploads/2020/09/screen-shot-2020-08-18-at-1.27.54-pm.png?w=1024\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-1349\" /></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Then, following the documented procedure to create a Transit Connect (<a rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" href=\"https://docs.vmware.com/en/VMware-Cloud-on-AWS/index.html\" target=\"_blank\">found in the official M.11 docs here</a>), we created a SDDC Group and worked with the customer\'s AWS team to accept the request to attach to their DX GW.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:jetpack/tiled-gallery {\"columnWidths\":[[100],[51.832122621451205,48.167877378548795]],\"ids\":[1352,1351,1350]} -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-jetpack-tiled-gallery aligncenter is-style-rectangular\"><div class=\"tiled-gallery__gallery\"><div class=\"tiled-gallery__row\"><div class=\"tiled-gallery__col\" style=\"flex-basis:100%;\"><figure class=\"tiled-gallery__item\"><img alt=\"\" data-height=\"439\" data-id=\"1352\" data-link=\"https://occasional-it.com/2020/09/21/the-great-convergence-hcx-over-transit-connect/screen-shot-2020-08-18-at-1-31-35-pm/\" data-url=\"http://localhost:8080/wp-content/uploads/2020/09/screen-shot-2020-08-18-at-1.31.35-pm.png\" data-width=\"986\" src=\"http://localhost:8080/wp-content/uploads/2020/09/screen-shot-2020-08-18-at-1.31.35-pm.png\" /></figure></div></div><div class=\"tiled-gallery__row\"><div class=\"tiled-gallery__col\" style=\"flex-basis:51.832122621451%;\"><figure class=\"tiled-gallery__item\"><img alt=\"\" data-height=\"557\" data-id=\"1351\" data-link=\"https://occasional-it.com/2020/09/21/the-great-convergence-hcx-over-transit-connect/screen-shot-2020-08-18-at-1-31-22-pm/\" data-url=\"http://localhost:8080/wp-content/uploads/2020/09/screen-shot-2020-08-18-at-1.31.22-pm.png\" data-width=\"983\" src=\"http://localhost:8080/wp-content/uploads/2020/09/screen-shot-2020-08-18-at-1.31.22-pm.png\" /></figure></div><div class=\"tiled-gallery__col\" style=\"flex-basis:48.167877378549%;\"><figure class=\"tiled-gallery__item\"><img alt=\"\" data-height=\"405\" data-id=\"1350\" data-link=\"https://occasional-it.com/2020/09/21/the-great-convergence-hcx-over-transit-connect/screen-shot-2020-08-18-at-1-31-09-pm/\" data-url=\"http://localhost:8080/wp-content/uploads/2020/09/screen-shot-2020-08-18-at-1.31.09-pm.png\" data-width=\"664\" src=\"http://localhost:8080/wp-content/uploads/2020/09/screen-shot-2020-08-18-at-1.31.09-pm.png\" /></figure></div></div></div></div>\n<!-- /wp:jetpack/tiled-gallery -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>It was remarkably simple and easy - granted the customer already had both their DX and their DX GW configured - but nonetheless I was very pleased with the ease of the implementation.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Then we proceeded to deploy HCX as normal (again - see some of the above links for a thorough overview of HCX deployment).  We had to make 2 changes to the HCX deployment:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list {\"ordered\":true} -->\n<ol><li>We had to ensure name resolution for HCX resolved to private IP addresses (configured through the SDDC Settings page).</li><li>When configuring the HCX Service Mesh we had to use the Direct Connect network profile for the cloud-side HCX configuration.</li></ol>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":1354,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"http://localhost:8080/wp-content/uploads/2020/09/screen-shot-2020-08-18-at-11.50.39-am.png?w=1024\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-1354\" /></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":1353,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"http://localhost:8080/wp-content/uploads/2020/09/screen-shot-2020-08-18-at-11.48.22-am.png?w=1024\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-1353\" /></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Once that was done, the appliances deployed and configured their tunnels with zero issues.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":1355,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"http://localhost:8080/wp-content/uploads/2020/09/screen-shot-2020-08-18-at-12.00.31-pm.png?w=1024\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-1355\" /></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>You can see below there is a new dashboard for reviewing routes learned and advertised over the Transit Connect - \"SDDC Interconnectivity\" - and all the routes came up very quickly.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":1348,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"http://localhost:8080/wp-content/uploads/2020/09/screen-shot-2020-08-18-at-1.27.16-pm.png?w=1024\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-1348\" /></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>You can find a great set of instructions for <a rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" href=\"https://vmc-onboarding.com/guide/4.-deploy-add-ons/hcx-hybrid-cloud-connect/\" target=\"_blank\">deploying HCX here as part of the public onboarding documentation.</a></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The key takeaway here is that <strong><em>deploying HCX over VMware Transit Connect is exactly the same as deploying with a Direct Connect Private VIF.</em></strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>I was super pleased with the experience, and the work that has been accomplished by the joint VMware and AWS teams.  Hopefully you will have a chance to try out this solution yourself!</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','The Great convergence - HCX over VMW Transit connect','','publish','open','open','','the-great-convergence-hcx-over-transit-connect','','','2020-09-21 16:23:24','2020-09-21 20:23:24','',0,'http://occasional-it.com/?p=1344',0,'post','',0),(1347,2,'2020-09-21 09:25:28','2020-09-21 13:25:28','','Screen Shot 2020-07-29 at 3.20.49 PM','','inherit','open','closed','','screen-shot-2020-07-29-at-3-20-49-pm','','','2020-09-21 09:25:28','2020-09-21 13:25:28','',1344,'http://localhost:8080/wp-content/uploads/2020/09/screen-shot-2020-07-29-at-3.20.49-pm.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(1348,2,'2020-09-21 09:25:31','2020-09-21 13:25:31','','Screen Shot 2020-08-18 at 1.27.16 PM','','inherit','open','closed','','screen-shot-2020-08-18-at-1-27-16-pm','','','2020-09-21 09:25:31','2020-09-21 13:25:31','',1344,'http://localhost:8080/wp-content/uploads/2020/09/screen-shot-2020-08-18-at-1.27.16-pm.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(1349,2,'2020-09-21 09:25:33','2020-09-21 13:25:33','','Screen Shot 2020-08-18 at 1.27.54 PM','','inherit','open','closed','','screen-shot-2020-08-18-at-1-27-54-pm','','','2020-09-21 09:25:33','2020-09-21 13:25:33','',1344,'http://localhost:8080/wp-content/uploads/2020/09/screen-shot-2020-08-18-at-1.27.54-pm.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(1350,2,'2020-09-21 09:25:35','2020-09-21 13:25:35','','Screen Shot 2020-08-18 at 1.31.09 PM','','inherit','open','closed','','screen-shot-2020-08-18-at-1-31-09-pm','','','2020-09-21 09:25:35','2020-09-21 13:25:35','',1344,'http://localhost:8080/wp-content/uploads/2020/09/screen-shot-2020-08-18-at-1.31.09-pm.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(1351,2,'2020-09-21 09:25:37','2020-09-21 13:25:37','','Screen Shot 2020-08-18 at 1.31.22 PM','','inherit','open','closed','','screen-shot-2020-08-18-at-1-31-22-pm','','','2020-09-21 09:25:37','2020-09-21 13:25:37','',1344,'http://localhost:8080/wp-content/uploads/2020/09/screen-shot-2020-08-18-at-1.31.22-pm.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(1352,2,'2020-09-21 09:25:39','2020-09-21 13:25:39','','Screen Shot 2020-08-18 at 1.31.35 PM','','inherit','open','closed','','screen-shot-2020-08-18-at-1-31-35-pm','','','2020-09-21 09:25:39','2020-09-21 13:25:39','',1344,'http://localhost:8080/wp-content/uploads/2020/09/screen-shot-2020-08-18-at-1.31.35-pm.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(1353,2,'2020-09-21 09:25:41','2020-09-21 13:25:41','','Screen Shot 2020-08-18 at 11.48.22 AM','','inherit','open','closed','','screen-shot-2020-08-18-at-11-48-22-am','','','2020-09-21 09:25:41','2020-09-21 13:25:41','',1344,'http://localhost:8080/wp-content/uploads/2020/09/screen-shot-2020-08-18-at-11.48.22-am.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(1354,2,'2020-09-21 09:25:43','2020-09-21 13:25:43','','Screen Shot 2020-08-18 at 11.50.39 AM','','inherit','open','closed','','screen-shot-2020-08-18-at-11-50-39-am','','','2020-09-21 09:25:43','2020-09-21 13:25:43','',1344,'http://localhost:8080/wp-content/uploads/2020/09/screen-shot-2020-08-18-at-11.50.39-am.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(1355,2,'2020-09-21 09:25:45','2020-09-21 13:25:45','','Screen Shot 2020-08-18 at 12.00.31 PM','','inherit','open','closed','','screen-shot-2020-08-18-at-12-00-31-pm','','','2020-09-21 09:25:45','2020-09-21 13:25:45','',1344,'http://localhost:8080/wp-content/uploads/2020/09/screen-shot-2020-08-18-at-12.00.31-pm.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(1368,2,'2020-09-21 15:40:43','2020-09-21 19:40:43','','Thor-The-Dark-World-Convergence','','inherit','open','closed','','thor-the-dark-world-convergence','','','2020-09-21 15:40:43','2020-09-21 19:40:43','',1344,'http://localhost:8080/wp-content/uploads/2020/09/thor-the-dark-world-convergence.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(1384,2,'2020-12-11 17:55:52','2020-12-11 22:55:52','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>This post was jointly authored by Tom Twyman (VMware) and Johnson Cauthon (Pureport).</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>Disclaimer</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong><em>This does not represent an official support statement by either VMware or Pureport.  The testing scenarios described were attempted simply to validate expected functionality - all configurations were completed by following public documentation. </em></strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>Overview</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>As customers expand their services and continue to adopt cloud services, it is becoming more and more common for them to adopt a multi-cloud stance.&nbsp; This enables them to embrace services from multiple cloud vendors, adopting the service(s) most appropriate for the use case at the time.&nbsp; However, this also presents a problem for the customer ‚Äì how does one adopt services from multiple cloud providers, and allow traffic to flow between those services in a high-throughput, low-latency, and secure fashion without requiring all that traffic to ‚Äòtrombone‚Äô or ‚Äòhairpin‚Äô to the customer datacenter for appropriate routing?&nbsp; The answer is a multi-cloud network fabric ‚Äì in this blog we will examine how we can accomplish this using Pureport MultiCloud Fabric.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>Environment Overview</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":1415,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\",\"linkDestination\":\"none\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"http://localhost:8080/wp-content/uploads/2020/12/pureport-testing.png?w=1024\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-1415\" /></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The diagram above represents a reference architecture for a customer that desires the ability to use the Pureport Multicloud Fabric to enable east-west communications between multiple cloud providers without requiring the traffic to route back to their on-premises routing infrastructure to do so.&nbsp; In this diagram we see the customer has provisioned environments for Google Cloud Platform, Amazon Web services, and VMware Cloud on AWS as well.&nbsp; Pureport provides connectivity to all the hyperscalers via a network fabric in a regional cross-connect facility. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Relevant networking information depicted above is as follows:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>GCP:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li>VPC with CIDR 172.24.0.0/16</li><li>Virtual machine with 172.16.0.2 provisioned</li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>AWS:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li>VPC with CIDR 172.28.0.0/16</li><li>EC2 instance with 172.28.0.240 provisioned</li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>VMC on AWS:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li>Management CIDR: 10.2.0.0/16 (used by vCenter, ESXi, and NSX)</li><li>Compute Segment of 10.3.2.0/24 (with DHCP)</li><li>Virtual machines provisioned:</li><li>Photon OS: 10.3.2.100 (DHCP)</li><li>CentOS with Wordpress:10.3.2.101</li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>AWS ‚ÄòLinked‚Äô VPC:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li>VPC with CIDR 172.32.0.0/16</li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Customer Prem Location (Raleigh, NC ‚Äì connected via Pureport VPN):</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li>DMZ network 172.16.1.0/24</li><li>Pingable endpoint: 172.16.1.2</li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Note that although Microsoft Azure was not included in this testing, there is every reason to believe it would operate functionally equivalent to the other cloud platforms included in this test.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>Viewing the Pureport Multicloud Fabric</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Below we see an overview of the entire network in the customer‚Äôs Pureport console.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":1409,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\",\"linkDestination\":\"none\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"http://localhost:8080/wp-content/uploads/2020/12/image-19.png?w=652\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-1409\" /></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Note</strong>:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li>Cloud capacity for AWS and VMware Cloud on AWS are provisioned in us-west-2 (Oregon), while the network point-of-presence (POP) is Seattle.</li><li>This causes network latency between cloud environments of about 15 ms (see ping tests below).</li><li>Similar deployments in other cloud regions will yield different results, based on proximity of POP to cloud datacenters.</li><li>For example, <strong><em>a similar setup in us-east-1 (N. VA) would likely yield response times closer to 2-3 ms.</em></strong></li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>BGP routing table viewed from customer-prem-facing Pureport routing gateway:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":1408,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\",\"linkDestination\":\"none\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"http://localhost:8080/wp-content/uploads/2020/12/image-18.png?w=364\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-1408\" /></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>BGP routing table viewed from the Google-facing Pureport routing gateway:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":1407,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\",\"linkDestination\":\"none\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"http://localhost:8080/wp-content/uploads/2020/12/image-17.png?w=364\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-1407\" /></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>BGP routing tabled viewed from Pureport gateway attached to the AWS Native environment:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":1406,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\",\"linkDestination\":\"none\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"http://localhost:8080/wp-content/uploads/2020/12/image-16.png?w=346\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-1406\" /></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>BGP routing table viewed from Pureport gateway attached to the VMC SDDC:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":1405,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\",\"linkDestination\":\"none\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"http://localhost:8080/wp-content/uploads/2020/12/image-15.png?w=350\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-1405\" /></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>Connect Your SDDCs with VMware Transit Connect</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>VMware Cloud on AWS provides multiple connectivity options for a customer\'s software defined datacenter (SDDC).  For any single SDDC, either a VPN connection or a Direct Connect virtual interface (VIF) may be configured.  However, in the event a customer needs to either connect multiple VMware Cloud SDDCs together - OR they need or desire high-throughput / low latency connectivity to other native AWS VPCs, or even other cloud providers, one may also leverage VMware Transit Connect.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>VMware Transit Connect was released earlier this year as a method to provide connectivity to a VMware-managed AWS Transit Gateway (vTGW) at native attachment speeds up to 50 Gbps.  <a rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" href=\"https://www.gilles.cloud/2020/06/vmware-cloud-on-aws-managed-transit.html\" target=\"_blank\">Gilles Chekroun has blogged extensively about Transit Connect here</a>.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>A VMC SDDC may be connected to the vTGW via an SDDC Group - follow the instructions in VMware‚Äôs documentation to create your SDDC Group.&nbsp; You may find the documentation here: <a rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" href=\"https://docs.vmware.com/en/VMware-Cloud-on-AWS/services/com.vmware.vmc-aws-operations/GUID-C957DBA7-16F5-412B-BB72-15B49B714723.html\" target=\"_blank\">https://docs.vmware.com/en/VMware-Cloud-on-AWS/services/com.vmware.vmc-aws-operations/GUID-C957DBA7-16F5-412B-BB72-15B49B714723.html</a></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Note that any SDDCs that are members of the SDDC group are automatically connected to a VMware-managed Transit Gateway behind the scenes.  This is depicted in the graphic above as the green-colored TGW icon.&nbsp; This allows for seamless east-west connectivity between SDDCs in the cloud via a high-speed, low-latency connection at 50 Gbps.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>Provide External Connectivity over Direct Connect</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>To allow connectivity to the rest of the environment ‚Äì including other VPCs in AWS, or other cloud providers, the Transit Connect must be connected to a AWS Direct Connect Gateway, as seen in the environment diagram above.  To complete this task a Direct Connect and Direct Connect Gateway must be provisioned in the customer\'s AWS account - this can be accomplished natively in the customer\'s AWS console or via the Pureport console.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Once the DX and DXGW have been provisioned, the VMware Transit Connect may be connected to the external DXGW.  To connect your Transit Connect and SDDC group to your Direct Connect Gateway, view your SDDC Group in the VMware Cloud Console.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Click on ‚ÄúDirect Connect Gateway\" and then click \"Add Account.\"</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":1418,\"width\":672,\"height\":385,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\",\"linkDestination\":\"none\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large is-resized\"><img src=\"http://localhost:8080/wp-content/uploads/2020/12/screen-shot-2020-12-11-at-12.17.01-pm-1.png?w=1024\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-1418\" width=\"672\" height=\"385\" /></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Enter the ID of your DXGW, as well as the AWS account ID, and the network prefixes you will allow for outgoing communication from your SDDC:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":1402,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\",\"linkDestination\":\"none\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"http://localhost:8080/wp-content/uploads/2020/12/image-13.png?w=294\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-1402\" /></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Your new connection to the DXGW will show as ‚ÄúREQUESTED.‚Äù</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":1401,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\",\"linkDestination\":\"none\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"http://localhost:8080/wp-content/uploads/2020/12/image-12.png?w=654\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-1401\" /></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In your AWS console, you will see the pending request for the Direct Connect Gateway:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":1400,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\",\"linkDestination\":\"none\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"http://localhost:8080/wp-content/uploads/2020/12/image-11.png?w=572\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-1400\" /></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>You will need to accept the request - click the hyperlink for the DXGW showing the pending request.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":1399,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\",\"linkDestination\":\"none\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"http://localhost:8080/wp-content/uploads/2020/12/image-10.png?w=520\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-1399\" /></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Highlight the request, and click \"Accept.\"</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":1397,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\",\"linkDestination\":\"none\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"http://localhost:8080/wp-content/uploads/2020/12/image-9.png?w=560\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-1397\" /></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The proposal will appear, and you will need to confirm the advertised routes - click \"Accept Proposal.\"</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":1396,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\",\"linkDestination\":\"none\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"http://localhost:8080/wp-content/uploads/2020/12/image-8.png?w=560\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-1396\" /></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Once accepted, the state will change to ‚Äúassociating.‚Äù</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":1395,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\",\"linkDestination\":\"none\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"http://localhost:8080/wp-content/uploads/2020/12/image-7.png?w=746\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-1395\" /></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Back in your VMware cloud console, the connectivity status for your Transit Connect will change to ‚ÄúCONNECTED.‚Äù</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":1394,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\",\"linkDestination\":\"none\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"http://localhost:8080/wp-content/uploads/2020/12/image-6.png?w=616\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-1394\" /></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>And you should see any local networks in the SDDC advertised on the ‚ÄúRouting‚Äù tab:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":1392,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\",\"linkDestination\":\"none\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"http://localhost:8080/wp-content/uploads/2020/12/image-5.png?w=476\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-1392\" /></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Once BGP converges over the Direct Connect Gateway, you should begin to see networks advertised from the network provider ‚Äì in this case, we see the networks from the ‚Äòcustomer‚Äô datacenter, as well as from the native Google and AWS VPCs:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":1391,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\",\"linkDestination\":\"none\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"http://localhost:8080/wp-content/uploads/2020/12/image-4.png?w=868\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-1391\" /></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>Test Connectivity:</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>From the customer datacenter, we run a quick test to our Wordpress blog running in VMC on AWS:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":1390,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\",\"linkDestination\":\"none\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"http://localhost:8080/wp-content/uploads/2020/12/image-3.png?w=682\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-1390\" /></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>(Screen shot of Wordpress site from customer prem location)</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>From the Photon OS running in the VMware Cloud SDDC, we can also ping all the other environments, including the customer datacenter ‚Äì which in our test environment is actually connected via a VPN from Raleigh, NC ‚Äì while the cloud environments were created in Oregon (AWS) and Seattle, WA (Google).&nbsp; This is reflected in the significantly longer ping times to the 172.16.1.0/24 network shown below:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":1389,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\",\"linkDestination\":\"none\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"http://localhost:8080/wp-content/uploads/2020/12/image-2.png?w=514\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-1389\" /></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Note that all the response times for cloud-to-cloud services are only 15-16 milliseconds, while ping tests to the customer datacenter reflect a much longer RTT ‚Äì closer to 100 ms.&nbsp; By disabling the VPN to the customer datacenter in NC, we see the routes updated appropriately in the SDDC Group routing table:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":1388,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\",\"linkDestination\":\"none\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"http://localhost:8080/wp-content/uploads/2020/12/image-1.png?w=610\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-1388\" /></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>If we once again test ICMP RTT with ping to the other cloud services, we see the RTT remains 15-16 ms, confirming that traffic remains routed east-west within the Pureport multicloud fabric, and does not have to be routed back on prem:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":1387,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\",\"linkDestination\":\"none\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"http://localhost:8080/wp-content/uploads/2020/12/image.png?w=670\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-1387\" /></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>Conclusion</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>As you can see, leveraging a multi-cloud fabric from Pureport provides a robust and high-performance network fabric in the cloud.  This alleviates any concerns that may arise for cross-cloud routing, as all east-west traffic between cloud providers remains in the provider network fabric, rather than returning on premise for routing.  A multicloud fabric is an excellent addition to any customer\'s hybrid cloud strategy and journey.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Testing a multicloud fabric with Pureport and VMC on AWS','How does one adopt services from multiple cloud providers and allow traffic to flow between those services  without requiring all that traffic to ‚Äòtrombone‚Äô or ‚Äòhairpin‚Äô to the customer datacenter? In this post we will examine how we can accomplish this using Pureport MultiCloud Fabric.','publish','open','open','','testing-a-multicloud-fabric-with-pureport-and-vmc-on-aws','','','2020-12-11 17:55:52','2020-12-11 22:55:52','',0,'http://occasional-it.com/?p=1384',0,'post','',0),(1387,2,'2020-12-11 17:45:25','2020-12-11 22:45:25','','image','','inherit','open','closed','','image','','','2020-12-11 17:45:25','2020-12-11 22:45:25','',0,'http://localhost:8080/wp-content/uploads/2020/12/image.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(1388,2,'2020-12-11 17:45:43','2020-12-11 22:45:43','','image-1','','inherit','open','closed','','image-1','','','2020-12-11 17:45:43','2020-12-11 22:45:43','',0,'http://localhost:8080/wp-content/uploads/2020/12/image-1.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(1389,2,'2020-12-11 17:46:00','2020-12-11 22:46:00','','image-2','','inherit','open','closed','','image-2','','','2020-12-11 17:46:00','2020-12-11 22:46:00','',0,'http://localhost:8080/wp-content/uploads/2020/12/image-2.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(1390,2,'2020-12-11 17:46:10','2020-12-11 22:46:10','','image-3','','inherit','open','closed','','image-3','','','2020-12-11 17:46:10','2020-12-11 22:46:10','',0,'http://localhost:8080/wp-content/uploads/2020/12/image-3.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(1391,2,'2020-12-11 17:46:23','2020-12-11 22:46:23','','image-4','','inherit','open','closed','','image-4','','','2020-12-11 17:46:23','2020-12-11 22:46:23','',0,'http://loc