INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (1623,2,'2021-11-19 15:44:31','2021-11-19 20:44:31','','screen-shot-2021-11-19-at-3.41.01-pm-1','','inherit','open','closed','','screen-shot-2021-11-19-at-3-41-01-pm-1','','','2021-11-19 15:44:31','2021-11-19 20:44:31','',0,'http://localhost:8080/wp-content/uploads/2021/11/screen-shot-2021-11-19-at-3.41.01-pm-1.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(1625,2,'2021-11-19 15:44:57','2021-11-19 20:44:57','','screen-shot-2021-11-19-at-3.44.46-pm','','inherit','open','closed','','screen-shot-2021-11-19-at-3-44-46-pm','','','2021-11-19 15:44:57','2021-11-19 20:44:57','',0,'http://localhost:8080/wp-content/uploads/2021/11/screen-shot-2021-11-19-at-3.44.46-pm.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(1627,2,'2021-11-19 15:46:43','2021-11-19 20:46:43','','screen-shot-2021-11-19-at-3.46.31-pm','','inherit','open','closed','','screen-shot-2021-11-19-at-3-46-31-pm','','','2021-11-19 15:46:43','2021-11-19 20:46:43','',0,'http://localhost:8080/wp-content/uploads/2021/11/screen-shot-2021-11-19-at-3.46.31-pm.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(1630,2,'2021-11-19 16:02:43','2021-11-19 21:02:43','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>\"Rock, Paper, Scissors, Lizard, Spock\" is a variation of the children‚Äôs 3-way lock hand game called Rock Paper Scissors (or \'Roshambo\'). The \'Lizard Spock\' version of the game has been made popular by the television show \"Big Bang Theory.\"</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:embed {\"url\":\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Kov2G0GouBw\",\"type\":\"video\",\"providerNameSlug\":\"youtube\",\"responsive\":true,\"className\":\"wp-embed-aspect-4-3 wp-has-aspect-ratio\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-embed is-type-video is-provider-youtube wp-block-embed-youtube wp-embed-aspect-4-3 wp-has-aspect-ratio\"><div class=\"wp-block-embed__wrapper\">\nhttps://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Kov2G0GouBw\n</div></figure>\n<!-- /wp:embed -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 id=\"what-is-this-all-about\">What is this all about?</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>This is actually quite an old post for me - I probably wrote it initially about8 years ago, however I couldn\'t find it, and it turns out there were quite a few HTML statements in the original post I hadn\'t cleaned up that prevented it from displaying correctly, so I am refreshing it with new graphics and updated content.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>I decided to build a little application using Neo4J to 1) learn a bit of code and 2) show how to model RPSLS in a graph database.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 id=\"getting-started\">Getting Started</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Download Neo4j Desktop from the following location, and install it on your desktop / laptop:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><a href=\"https://neo4j.com/download/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">https://neo4j.com/download/</a></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Once installed, create a new local database, and open to the integrated browser.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":1610,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\",\"linkDestination\":\"none\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"http://localhost:8080/wp-content/uploads/2021/11/screen-shot-2021-11-19-at-12.37.02-pm.png?w=1024\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-1610\" /></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Use the statement below to populate the graph with the objects and relationships.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>CREATE p=(paper:object {name:\"paper\"})-&#091;:covers]-&gt;(rock:object {name:\"rock\"})-&#091;:crushes]-&gt;(scissors:object {name:\"scissors\"})-&#091;:decapitates]-&gt;(lizard:animal {name:\"lizard\"})-&#091;:poisons]-&gt;(spock:vulcan:person {name:\"spock\"})-&#091;:vaporizes]-&gt;(rock)-&#091;:crushes]-&gt;(lizard)-&#091;:eats]-&gt;(paper)-&#091;:disproves]-&gt;(spock)-&#091;:smashes]-&gt;(scissors)-&#091;:cuts]-&gt;(paper)</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":1612,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\",\"linkDestination\":\"none\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"http://localhost:8080/wp-content/uploads/2021/11/screen-shot-2021-11-19-at-12.40.07-pm.png?w=1024\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-1612\" /></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 id=\"if-you-need-to\">If you need to...</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Use the code below at any time to wipe the database and start over‚Ä¶‚Äã</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>MATCH (n)\nDETACH DELETE (n)</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 id=\"explore-the-graph\">Explore the Graph</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Let\'s take a look at what we\'ve got...</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>// Get some data\nMATCH (n1)-&#091;r]-&gt;(n2) RETURN r, n1, n2 LIMIT 25</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":1615,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\",\"linkDestination\":\"none\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"http://localhost:8080/wp-content/uploads/2021/11/screen-shot-2021-11-19-at-3.33.18-pm.png?w=1024\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-1615\" /></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 id=\"find-all-objects\">What if....</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p id=\"find-all-objects\">We only wanted to see objects of type \'object?\'</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:preformatted -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-preformatted\">match (n:object) return n</pre>\n<!-- /wp:preformatted -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":1616,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\",\"linkDestination\":\"none\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"http://localhost:8080/wp-content/uploads/2021/11/screen-shot-2021-11-19-at-3.36.50-pm.png?w=822\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-1616\" /></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4 id=\"find-all-non-objects\">Find all non-objects</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:preformatted -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-preformatted\">match (n) where NOT (n:object) return n</pre>\n<!-- /wp:preformatted -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":1617,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\",\"linkDestination\":\"none\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"http://localhost:8080/wp-content/uploads/2021/11/screen-shot-2021-11-19-at-3.39.10-pm.png?w=1024\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-1617\" /></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4 id=\"find-all-vulcans\">Find all vulcans</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:preformatted -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-preformatted\">match (n:vulcan) return n</pre>\n<!-- /wp:preformatted -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":1619,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\",\"linkDestination\":\"none\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"http://localhost:8080/wp-content/uploads/2021/11/screen-shot-2021-11-19-at-3.39.44-pm.png?w=740\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-1619\" /></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4 id=\"what-are-the-actions-for-rock\">What are the actions for Rock?</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:preformatted -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-preformatted\">MATCH (n:object{name:\"rock\"})-[r]-&gt;(x)\nreturn n,r,x</pre>\n<!-- /wp:preformatted -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":1621,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\",\"linkDestination\":\"none\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"http://localhost:8080/wp-content/uploads/2021/11/screen-shot-2021-11-19-at-3.41.01-pm.png?w=978\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-1621\" /></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4 id=\"what-are-the-actions-for-paper\">What are the actions for Paper?</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:preformatted -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-preformatted\">MATCH (n:object{name:\"paper\"})-[rel]-&gt;x\nreturn n,r,x</pre>\n<!-- /wp:preformatted -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":1625,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\",\"linkDestination\":\"none\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"http://localhost:8080/wp-content/uploads/2021/11/screen-shot-2021-11-19-at-3.44.46-pm.png?w=1024\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-1625\" /></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4 id=\"what-are-the-actions-for-spock\">What are the actions for Spock?</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:preformatted -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-preformatted\">MATCH (n:vulcan{name:\"Spock\"})-[r]-&gt;x\nreturn n,r,x</pre>\n<!-- /wp:preformatted -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":1627,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\",\"linkDestination\":\"none\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"http://localhost:8080/wp-content/uploads/2021/11/screen-shot-2021-11-19-at-3.46.31-pm.png?w=1024\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-1627\" /></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Rock, Paper, Scissors, Lizard, Spock','','publish','open','open','','rock-paper-scissors-lizard-spock','','','2021-11-19 16:02:43','2021-11-19 21:02:43','',0,'https://occasional-it.com/?p=1630',0,'post','',0),(1633,2,'2021-12-01 16:07:35','2021-12-01 21:07:35','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>What does refactoring mean?</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Why might you need or want to refactor?  </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Cost optimization?  </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Availability?  </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Scalability? </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Performance?</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Is ‚Äúrelocation‚Äù a reasonable strategy?</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','What is ‚Äúrefactoring?‚Äù','','draft','open','open','','','','','2021-12-01 16:07:35','2021-12-01 21:07:35','',0,'http://occasional-it.com/?p=1633',0,'post','',0),(1640,2,'2022-08-31 12:23:45','2022-08-31 16:23:45','','1661915688135','','inherit','open','closed','','1661915688135','','','2022-08-31 12:23:45','2022-08-31 16:23:45','',1790,'http://localhost:8080/wp-content/uploads/2022/08/1661915688135.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(1648,2,'2022-11-01 12:01:21','2022-11-01 16:01:21','','Erupting Prominence Observed by SDO on March 30, 2010','<a href=\"https://www.flickr.com/photos/24662369@N07/4540790225\" rel=\"nofollow\">Erupting Prominence Observed by SDO on March 30, 2010</a> by <a href=\"https://www.flickr.com/photos/24662369@N07\" rel=\"nofollow\">NASA Goddard Photo and Video</a> is licensed under <a href=\"https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/2.0/\" rel=\"nofollow\">CC-BY 2.0</a>','inherit','open','closed','','4540790225_9ceae82f86_b','','','2022-11-01 12:01:21','2022-11-01 16:01:21','',0,'http://localhost:8080/wp-content/uploads/2022/11/4540790225_9ceae82f86_b.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(1650,2,'2023-05-17 09:46:44','2023-05-17 13:46:44','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Today I am really quite happy to share the latest release of the Python Client for VMware Cloud on AWS - version 2.0!  This represents several months worth of work, as well as over 200 commits, over 5000 lines of new code, over 30 new commands, and support for some of the latest innovations in VMware Cloud on AWS, such as:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Creating a SDDC!</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Secondary T1 gateways!</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>T1 VPN!</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Fixed and Flexible network segments!</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>NSX Advanced Firewall IDS and IPS!</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>VMware Transit Connect attachments to DXGW and VPC!</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>FlexCompute (experimental)!</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Additionally, we spent a TON of time restructuring the project into multiple modules, and refactoring all the functions to leverage a mature python module for argument handling - argparse.  Leveraging argparse gives us the flexibility to handle user input in a much more elegant way than just using sys.argv, plus it is self-documenting, making it much easier to troubleshoot, extend, and change functions in the future.  Finally, pretty much all the logic for how to manipulate data, return data to the user, error handling, etc has been moved to a \'functions\' module, which allows us to keep all the code <strong><em>directly</em></strong> related to API functionality separate.  The new project structure is laid out somewhat as follows:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":1769,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\",\"linkDestination\":\"none\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"http://localhost:8080/wp-content/uploads/2023/05/pyvmc_refactor-1.png?w=1024\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-1769\" /></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>While this is of course a community-supported project, and not an \'official\' VMware product, nonetheless I am still very proud of the work the team has put in.  This has been a fantastic learning opportunity for me, and I am looking forward to continuing to add features and functionality in the months ahead.  </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>You can find the official release on the <a href=\"https://flings.vmware.com/python-client-for-vmc-on-aws\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">VMware Flings site here.</a></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>You can find the <a href=\"https://github.com/vmware/python-client-for-vmware-cloud-on-aws\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">source code on Github</a> here (including instructions on contributing to the project).</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Building a CLI for VMware Cloud on AWS','','publish','open','open','','building-a-cli-for-vmware-cloud-on-aws','','','2023-05-17 09:46:44','2023-05-17 13:46:44','',0,'https://occasional-it.com/?p=1650',0,'post','',0),(1652,2,'2022-12-23 10:55:04','2022-12-23 15:55:04','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>One of the most frequently asked questions I get from customers is, \"How can I recover my virtual machines without having to change their IP address(es)?\"</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>An EXCELLENT question.  I like to tell my customers we have a very rich toolkit, which may be used to build the type of solution they would like to use for whatever they would like!  And while this is true... it\'s not very helpful.  Therefore, last year one of my colleagues - the great <a href=\"https://www.linkedin.com/in/eskander-mirza-a478653/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">Eskander Mirza</a> - and I put together some tests using VMware Cloud Disaster Recovery and VMware HCX, to try to provide some concrete guidance.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":1662,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\",\"linkDestination\":\"none\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"http://localhost:8080/wp-content/uploads/2022/12/1-solution_overview-vmw-brand.png?w=1024\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-1662\" /></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Essentially, the document we wrote runs through several scenarios - 5 scenarios for actual outages, and 3 for testing purposes - to try and demonstrate what one can / should expect when using HCX stretched networking with VMware Cloud Disaster recovery.  Based on some information from the HCX team I had to rewrite large sections of it this past summer, but I am happy to say it has been once again re-released on VMware\'s Tech Zone for VMware Cloud on AWS.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Essentially, the document lays out - with diagrams - 5 scenarios for running a recovery in different outage situations:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list {\"ordered\":true} -->\n<ol><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Complete outage of the source site</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Outage of the WAN / internet</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Outage of a specific workload or application</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Outage of specific on-premise networks or segments</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Outage of the VMware HCX Infrastructure itself</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ol>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In each section we run through what one might expect to happen, how to execute your recovery, and what actions (if any) you might need to take to ensure your stretched network provides connectivity for your workloads as desired.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":1666,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\",\"linkDestination\":\"none\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"http://localhost:8080/wp-content/uploads/2022/12/failure_scenario_1.png?w=1024\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-1666\" /></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Then we run through three specific testing scenarios:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list {\"ordered\":true} -->\n<ol><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Performing a test recovery with changed workload IP address</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Performing a test recovery into a <em>routed</em> network with the same IP address</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Performing a test recovery into an <em>isolated</em> network with the same IP address</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ol>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>All tests / outages were performed, as you might imagine, in a controlled, clean, lab environment, and therefore you are assured to have to make accommodations for your own networks / environments.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>You can find the document here: <br /><a href=\"https://vmc.techzone.vmware.com/resource/using-vmware-cloud-disaster-recovery-and-hcx-stretched-networks\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">https://vmc.techzone.vmware.com/resource/using-vmware-cloud-disaster-recovery-and-hcx-stretched-networks</a></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Happy reading!</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Using HCX stretched networks for disaster recovery','','publish','open','open','','using-hcx-stretched-networks-for-disaster-recovery','','','2022-12-23 10:55:04','2022-12-23 15:55:04','',0,'https://occasional-it.com/?p=1652',0,'post','',0),(1662,2,'2022-12-23 09:57:56','2022-12-23 14:57:56','','1-solution_overview-vmw-brand','','inherit','open','closed','','1-solution_overview-vmw-brand','','','2022-12-23 09:57:56','2022-12-23 14:57:56','',1652,'http://localhost:8080/wp-content/uploads/2022/12/1-solution_overview-vmw-brand.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(1665,2,'2022-12-23 09:59:40','2022-12-23 14:59:40','','figure1-solution overview','','inherit','open','closed','','figure1-solution-overview','','','2022-12-23 09:59:40','2022-12-23 14:59:40','',1652,'http://localhost:8080/wp-content/uploads/2022/12/figure1-solution-overview.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(1666,2,'2022-12-23 10:00:14','2022-12-23 15:00:14','','failure_scenario_1','','inherit','open','closed','','failure_scenario_1','','','2022-12-23 10:00:14','2022-12-23 15:00:14','',1652,'http://localhost:8080/wp-content/uploads/2022/12/failure_scenario_1.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(1668,2,'2022-12-28 16:19:38','2022-12-28 21:19:38','<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">...but is it for play or production?</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Some time back, one of my colleagues scheduled a call between myself and several sellers (sales representatives) from Amazon Web Services (AWS).  These are/were sales reps or account executives at AWS either selling the entire AWS portfolio or focused specifically on VMware Cloud on AWS.  They posed a fairly straightforward question to me... </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong><em>\"Why is this so hard?\"</em></strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Over the past 4 years I have received many questions similar in nature...</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>\"Why does it take so long?\"</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>\"Why does it cost so much?\"</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>\"Why is it so complicated?\"</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>\"Why is the networking so complex?\"</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>\"Why can\'t we do this faster?\"<br /></li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>You can see there is a trend here somewhere...  Essentially, the team wanted to understand why customers aren\'t able to \"move to the cloud\" as fast as they want.... After all, a developer can log into AWS and build something in minutes or hours, right?  Everything is built with an API, so you can automate it all, right?  AWS has everything you need to build anything you want, right?  </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>So if I have a number of applications I want to move from my own data center out to the \'cloud,\' why does it take so long?</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Indeed, AWS, Azure, Google - all of them have a powerful array of readily available infrastructure and application services.  An infrastructure administrator or a developer can log into the cloud console and deploy a new service or application in minutes or hours.  If you take advantage of advanced capabilities such as AWS CloudFormation templates, or leverage an API through a framework such as Terraform, this time can be reduced dramatically. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Yet over and over, what I have observed is once a customer has made the decision to go \"all in\" on cloud, invariably it takes longer and is significantly harder than they expect... and frequently significantly more expensive.  This differs<strong><em> wildly</em></strong> from the perception (and advertisement) that \'cloud\' is <em>easy, fast, and cheap.</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":1685,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\",\"linkDestination\":\"none\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"http://localhost:8080/wp-content/uploads/2022/12/image-header_park.jpg?w=1000\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-1685\" /></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>After all, for those of us that work in IT - either as developers or as infrastructure admins - who hasn\'t taken a class, spun up a free instance of something in AWS / Azure / Google, and later been able to declare - \"Hey look!  I built something!\"  It is <strong><em>absolutely true</em></strong> that the \'cloud\' offers an abundance of building blocks that are immediately available to help you build something new.  And that right there is the major difference - are you building something new, or are you looking to \'cloudify\' something that already exists?  To understand this further, I propose we examine the problem through the lens of both use cases.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Building something new</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>As a cloud user, if I am building something new, how am I likely to start?  Probably I will sign up for a free account, and deploy a bunch of infrastructure or application services that will incur no charges (or very minimal costs).  I can deploy new services at will, frequently with no regard or thought to my corporation\' security posture, governance, billing, networking strategy, IP scheme, and so on.  This works for me because after all, most likely I am learning about the capabilities of the service(s), and trying to prove out an idea.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":1682,\"width\":512,\"height\":288,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\",\"linkDestination\":\"none\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large is-resized\"><img src=\"http://localhost:8080/wp-content/uploads/2022/12/yellow-wrangler.png?w=1024\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-1682\" width=\"512\" height=\"288\" /></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong><em>After</em></strong> I have built a thing, <strong><em>after</em></strong> I have proven out my idea for how a system or application may be built in the cloud... <strong><em>then</em></strong> I can think and worry about all those other things.  First Gartner, then AWS have built out a <a rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" href=\"https://aws.amazon.com/blogs/enterprise-strategy/6-strategies-for-migrating-applications-to-the-cloud/\" target=\"_blank\">framework of strategies for migrating applications</a> to the cloud - rehost, replatform, repurchase, refactor, retire, retain. Once I have proven an idea, I can then start to discuss with my company what strategy makes the most sense.  It is at this point we start to discuss \'landing zones,\' building out an account structure for use with the corporation and other users, working through the billing / cost structure, network connectivity, IP addressing, resilience and disaster recovery, etc.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In other words, it is <strong><em>at this point</em></strong> that things slow wwwaaayyyy down.  </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Essentially the company has to embrace the idea of building a new data center... in the cloud... on someone else\'s physical infrastructure.  As you might imagine this poses a LOT of challenges that many customers struggle with.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":1681,\"width\":512,\"height\":484,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\",\"linkDestination\":\"none\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large is-resized\"><img src=\"http://localhost:8080/wp-content/uploads/2022/12/yellow-wrangler-mud.png?w=1024\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-1681\" width=\"512\" height=\"484\" /><figcaption class=\"wp-element-caption\">Confidence is what you have before you understand the situation...</figcaption></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The lesson here?  <strong><em>So long as you are not required to actually put something into production</em></strong> - the cloud is <em>easy, fast, and (sometimes) cheap.</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Working with existing systems</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>On the other hand, if your goal is to move existing systems / applications to the cloud - regardless of your \"R\" selection - much of that hard work must \'shift left.\'  In other words, we have to take all that corporate governance, process, security, networking, resilience, etc, and dddrrraaggg it to the front of the process.  After all, you can\'t reasonably take something that is currently processing transactions for your business and just move it without thinking through the implications to networking, security, connectivity, access, performance, etc.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>For a company that has not yet addressed how to do business in the cloud using these services, there is no way around it - you must do the hard work.  In my experience, it does not matter:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>how much technical debt has been eliminated on premises</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>how well your company has adopted DevOps / DevSecOps</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>how much automation you have adopted</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>et cetera...</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>You must extend your thinking, governance, security, connectivity, IP strategy, and so on to accommodate a new enclave of computing that previously was not available to you.  </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">A note about resilience</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>I want to focus for just a moment on resilience, as this is something of a confounding variable in the \"R\" conversation - particularly with existing applications.  None of the cloud providers really promise more than 99.9% availability of their services (with some exceptions like DNS, S3, etc).  the overriding presumption is that whatever you put out there must be able to tolerate any number of types of failures.... failure of the underlying physical host or components, networking, or even an entire data center or region.  This makes perfect logical sense - the infrastructure doesn\'t belong to your company, therefore every effort should be made to ensure your applications and services can survive multiple types of outages.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The obvious problem here is of course that over the past several decades literally the entire IT infrastructure industry has been innovating new ways to provide resilience for the infrastructure that is deployed in your company\'s data center.  Therefore, moving an existing application from your data center into the cloud also means giving up the inherent resilience built into the infrastructure on which your company has spent millions of dollars.  Where will that resilience come from?  How will you accomplish that in the cloud?</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Conclusion</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>It doesn\'t matter, really, which approach you take... You may need to spend some time learning what the cloud has to offer, and there are great, fast, easy, cheap (often free) ways to do so.  But putting something into production in the cloud is a very different affair that requires a great deal more consideration and planning.  Some platforms like VMware Cloud can accelerate <strong><em>some</em></strong> of that by providing many of the same infrastructure capabilities in the cloud that you benefit from on premise, and can therefore eliminate much of the time and complexity associated with refactoring or re-platforming an application.  Simply \'Relocate\' the application onto new VMware infrastructure in the cloud!</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>My two cents?   The takeaway here is that putting <strong><em>anything</em></strong> into production in the cloud is a fundamentally different challenge than just building something for test / dev / lab in the cloud.  Just because you can say \"Hey, mom - look, I built a thing!\" doesn\'t mean you are ready to move it into production.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Hey mom!  I built a thing!','OK - you want to leverage the cloud for your business... it is for play or production?  There are different things to consider depending on your approach.','publish','open','open','','hey-mom-i-built-a-thing','','','2022-12-28 16:19:38','2022-12-28 21:19:38','',0,'https://occasional-it.com/?p=1668',0,'post','',0),(1681,2,'2022-12-28 16:09:42','2022-12-28 21:09:42','','yellow-wrangler-mud','','inherit','open','closed','','yellow-wrangler-mud','','','2022-12-28 16:09:42','2022-12-28 21:09:42','',1668,'http://localhost:8080/wp-content/uploads/2022/12/yellow-wrangler-mud.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(1682,2,'2022-12-28 16:09:50','2022-12-28 21:09:50','','yellow-wrangler','','inherit','open','closed','','yellow-wrangler','','','2022-12-28 16:09:50','2022-12-28 21:09:50','',1668,'http://localhost:8080/wp-content/uploads/2022/12/yellow-wrangler.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(1685,2,'2022-12-28 16:18:35','2022-12-28 21:18:35','','image-header_park','','inherit','open','closed','','image-header_park','','','2022-12-28 16:18:35','2022-12-28 21:18:35','',1668,'http://localhost:8080/wp-content/uploads/2022/12/image-header_park.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(1690,2,'2023-01-17 16:23:16','0000-00-00 00:00:00','<!-- wp:image {\"id\":1692,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\",\"linkDestination\":\"none\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"http://localhost:8080/wp-content/uploads/2023/01/picture1.png?w=1024\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-1692\" /></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>‚ÄãCustomers evaluating our software often don‚Äôt know how to articulate ‚Äòwhat good looks like‚Äô ‚Äì in fact, they frequently ask us, ‚ÄúWhat do other customers do?‚Äù</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>‚ÄãOn the VMC team, we position and work with a variety of solutions‚Äì HCX, Horizon, SRM, vROps Cloud, vRLIC ‚Äì all of which require different techniques to evaluate a successful implementation.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>‚ÄãWithout a framework to approach how to define success, we run the risk of poorly defined criteria, which can lead to scope creep during a POC and reduce the chances of a positive outcome.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>‚ÄãWe need to provide a standardized approach to defining how our customers evaluate our solutions.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>‚ÄãSURGE represents a standardized data model and framework for defining and documenting success criteria for presales activities.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>‚ÄãBy providing a standardized approach for defining success during a POC, we can both constrain the evaluation activities and duration, and at the same time dramatically increase the likelihood of a positive outcome.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>‚ÄãQuestions you might ask your customer to help uncover custom / unique test cases:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>‚Ä¢Who is responsible for that solution?</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>‚Ä¢Do you have a team of folks prepared to perform the testing for that application?</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>‚Ä¢Do you have a functional test plan for accomplishing this?</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>‚Ä¢Exactly how will you establish that &lt;solution xyz&gt; will work correctly?</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>‚Ä¢What are the exact steps that will be used to verify functionality?</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":1} -->\n<h1 class=\"wp-block-heading\" id=\"title-text\"><a href=\"https://confluence.eng.vmware.com/pages/viewpage.action?pageId=875074378\">How we define and use \'Success Criteria\'</a></h1>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\" id=\"Howwedefineanduse\'SuccessCriteria\'-Whatare\'successcriteria?\'\">What are \'success criteria?\'</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>\'Success Criteria\' - what are they?¬† Essentially, \'success criteria\' are a set of data points used to measure success or failure of an effort.¬† While this can (obviously) be highly subjective relative to each customer, for any given technical solution usually this can be broken down into \'use cases,\' \'test cases,\' and \'requirements mapping.\'</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\" id=\"Howwedefineanduse\'SuccessCriteria\'-Whatisa\'usecase?\'\">What is a \'use case?\'</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>A \'<em><strong>use case</strong></em>\' is a business-aligned, IT outcome.&nbsp; VMware has identified the following high-level use cases for VMware Cloud:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Cloud Migrations - Application Specific</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Cloud Migrations - Data Center Wide</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Cloud Migrations - Infrastructure Refresh</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Data Center Extension - Test/Dev</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Data Center Extension - Footprint Expansion</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Data Center Extension - On-demand Capacity</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Data Center Extension - Virtual Desktops &amp; Published Apps</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Disaster Recovery - New DR</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Disaster Recovery - Compliment Existing DR</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Disaster Recovery - Replace Existing DR</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Next-Gen Apps - App Modernization</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Next-Gen Apps - Next Gen App Buildout</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Next-Gen Apps - Emerging Technologies</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Partner Solutions - Partner ISV Solutions</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Partner Solutions - Partner MSP/SISO/SOPRO Solutions</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\" id=\"Howwedefineanduse\'SuccessCriteria\'-Whatisa\'testcase?\'\">What is a \'test case?\'</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>A \'<em><strong>test case</strong></em>\' is a technical task (or series of tasks) that must be accomplished to demonstrate successful achievement of the <em><strong>use case.</strong></em> Cloud Solutions engineering has identified a number of common, repeatable test cases - specific to VMware Cloud - that form the basis of tasks necessary to demonstrate the above use cases.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Lacking anything provided by the customer, we (VMware) can provide some \'boilerplate\' success criteria related to the functionality of the solution.&nbsp; Arguably, the templated success criteria might better be defined as \'proof of functionality\' or \'functional test plans\' for the various aspects of VMware Cloud on AWS, HCX, Site Recovery, VCDR, etc.&nbsp; Ideally, the customer will have their own success criteria they bring to the discussion...</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>On the other hand, if they don\'t, we can proceed with ours - which we are fully in control of and capable of proving out.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Given the following use case - \"Cloud Migrations - Infrastructure Refresh,\" examples of <strong>test</strong><strong> cases</strong> are:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Provision cloud SDDC</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Basic connectivity</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Extend L2 Network</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Live Migration of Virtual Machine</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Replicate Virtual Machines to cloud - Vmware Site Recovery</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Cluster Load testing / Performance Benchmarking</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Application Load testing / performance benchmark</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>VM provisioning using automation</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Simulate failures / DR &amp; BCP scenarios</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>vRealize Operations integration</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Implementation of micro segmentation</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Encryption of data in transit / at rest ‚Äì SMB or NFS</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>While these are a listing of many of the possible tasks or actions associated with the aforementioned use case, note that a customer may not need or desire to prove or accomplish <em><strong>all</strong></em> of the above tasks.&nbsp; It is the responsibility of the Solution Architect to discuss, understand, and review the customer\'s business goals to help establish which test cases might be necessary to execute to demonstrate successful achievement of the use case.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\" id=\"Howwedefineanduse\'SuccessCriteria\'-CustomTestCases\">Custom Test Cases</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>It is entirely possible the customer has a need or desire beyond those test cases listed above. For example, they may desire to test a specific application running in VMware Cloud on AWS - it is then the responsibility of the customer to establish what the proper test cases might be to demonstrate acceptable functional performance of the application.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Questions you might ask your customer to help uncover these test cases:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Who is responsible for that solution?</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Do you have a team of folks prepared to perform the testing for that application?</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Do you have a functional test plan for accomplishing this?</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Exactly how will you establish that <em>&lt;solution xyz&gt;</em> will work correctly?&nbsp;</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>What are the exact steps that will be used to verify functionality?</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\" id=\"Howwedefineanduse\'SuccessCriteria\'-IntroducingNewTestCases\">Introducing New Test Cases</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>If you have documented a use case or test case that is broadly applicable to other customers - <strong>we want to hear about it!&nbsp;</strong> We can include it in the official list of repeatable test cases... <strong>just ask!</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\" id=\"Howwedefineanduse\'SuccessCriteria\'-Whatisa\'requirementmapping?\'\">What is a \'requirement mapping?\'</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>For any given use case and its associated test cases, there are a series of basic tasks that must be executed to be able to achieve the test case in question.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>For example, given the first test case above - \"Provision Cloud SDDC\" - we know the following tasks must be accomplished:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>VMware Account activated</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>AWS Account activated</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>AWS VPC created with necessary CIDR and subnets</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>SDDC created and connected to AWS VPC</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Note that requirement mappings are not necessarily a prescriptive, step-by-step, \"how-to\" guide (although they could be)... rather the requirement mappings we use in our pilot / POC guides are specific enough to inform the presales team and the customer what must be accomplished, yet not written as a \'how-to.\'</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','What are Success Criteria?','','draft','open','open','','','','','2023-01-17 16:23:16','0000-00-00 00:00:00','',0,'https://occasional-it.com/?p=1690',0,'post','',0),(1692,2,'2023-01-17 16:19:04','2023-01-17 21:19:04','','picture1','','inherit','open','closed','','picture1','','','2023-01-17 16:19:04','2023-01-17 21:19:04','',1690,'http://localhost:8080/wp-content/uploads/2023/01/picture1.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(1696,2,'2023-01-25 21:55:34','2023-01-26 02:55:34','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Introducing the <a href=\"https://github.com/vmware-samples/vmware-cloud-sizer-companion-cli\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">VMware Cloud Sizer Companion CLI</a>!  This is a python-based client that can be used to model workloads in VMware Cloud... quickly, easily, repeatedly, and reliably!</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Overview</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>I am really excited to introduce everyone to my latest passion project - the VMware Cloud Sizer Companion CLI!  (It\'s a clunky name, I know, but it is what it is!)   Admittedly, this is probably not something that will be interesting to everyone, but as a pre-sales solution architect I spend a LOT of time thinking about how to optimize a customer\'s cloud environment.  I have posted about my adventures with sizing workloads previously - <a href=\"https://occasional-it.com/2020/04/13/smart-sizing-1-data-collection/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">here</a>, <a href=\"https://occasional-it.com/2020/04/19/smart-sizing-2-analysis/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">here</a>, and <a href=\"https://occasional-it.com/2020/04/25/smart-sizing-3-real-life-examples/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">here</a>.  As I discussed in those articles, I frequently run multiple scenarios for any given engagement with a customer... evaluating powered on vs. off workloads, comparing used vs. provisioned storage and memory, splitting workloads between different clusters, etc.  I know this is something my colleagues in the partner community are also concerned with, so hopefully our friends in the partner ecosystem will find this useful as well.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>For those of you who aren\'t already aware, the <a rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" href=\"https://vmc.vmware.com/sizer\" target=\"_blank\">VMware Cloud Sizer</a> is the \'source of truth\' for modeling workloads against VMware Cloud on AWS (and soon, Google Cloud VMware Service, VMware Cloud on Equinix, and so on).  If you are considering migrating some virtual machines to VMware Cloud, this SHOULD be your first stop for understanding how large / small an environment you might need.  The VMware Cloud Sizer is a web-based interface that allows you to either model an environment quickly based on average VM characteristics, or to upload a collection file from RVTools or LiveOptics, as well as a host of additional features.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Supported Features</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Even though it\'s only a couple weeks old, the <a href=\"https://github.com/vmware-samples/vmware-cloud-sizer-companion-cli\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">VMware Cloud Sizer Companion CLI</a> already supports the following features:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list {\"ordered\":true} -->\n<ol><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Ingest either a LiveOptics or RVTools file</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Provide a quick review (\"view_only\") option to summarize the environment</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Retrieve a sizing recommendation for the environment</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Create workload profiles based on: <!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Current vm:cluster distribution - all clusters</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Current vm:cluster distribution - some clusters</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Guest OS based on text string filter</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>VM name based on text string filter</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list --></li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Include all VM, or only those powered on / suspended</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Present results on-screen<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Identify VM exceptions or host incompatibilities</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list --></li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Optionally save to PDF as well</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ol>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>There is a decent list of things yet to be introduced to the companion CLI:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>options for \'provisioned\' vs. \'consumed\' storage</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>powered on / off / suspended VM</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>selection / enforcement of specific host types</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>SDDC configuration options (appliance size, preferred FTT / FTM, etc.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>However, while it may not yet support all the features of the full Sizer web application, the benefit of using the VMware Cloud Sizer Companion CLI is that we have the opportunity to transform the data in any way we like before requesting a sizing recommendation!  For example, we can create workload profiles by cluster, VM Name, or Guest Operating system simply by using a text search string.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Getting help</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>To get help for the tool, simply run:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>./sizerimporter.py -h</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":1727,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\",\"linkDestination\":\"none\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"http://localhost:8080/wp-content/uploads/2023/01/2023-01-25_21-50-22.png?w=1024\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-1727\" /></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The workflow for the VMware Cloud Sizer Companion CLI is as follows:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Ingest a file</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Get an overview of the environment</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Select options to receive a sizing</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Select output options</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Get an overview of the environment</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Let\'s assume you have an RVTools file with the virtual machine data you want to use.  </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>First, get an overview of the environment:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>./sizerimporter.py -fn rvtools_file.xlsx -ft rv-tools -a view_only</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The returned data gives you an idea of what you are working with:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":1713,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\",\"linkDestination\":\"none\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"http://localhost:8080/wp-content/uploads/2023/01/2023-01-25_21-04-43.png?w=1024\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-1713\" /></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":1714,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\",\"linkDestination\":\"none\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"http://localhost:8080/wp-content/uploads/2023/01/2023-01-25_21-05-01.png?w=1024\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-1714\" /></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>You can see that you receive some information on the total number of VM, clusters, different operating systems, and some metrics about VPU, memory and VMDK configurations and utilization.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Getting a Default Sizing</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>You can very easily simply submit the data for a sizing recommendation as-is:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>./sizerimporter.py -fn rvtools_file.xlsx -ft rv-tools -a default</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>(get a PDF of the results just by adding \"--output_format PDF\" to your command)</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Here are the results - note that virtual machines that can not be placed or that can only be placed on certain host types are identified and called out:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":1718,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\",\"linkDestination\":\"none\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"http://localhost:8080/wp-content/uploads/2023/01/2023-01-25_21-09-52.png?w=1024\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-1718\" /></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Create workload profiles by cluster</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>If you prefer to maintain cluster separation as it already exists in the environment:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>./sizerimporter.py -fn rvtools_file.xlsx -ft rv-tools -a custom -wp clusters</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>And you can see it automagically separates workloads by cluster, and maintains current cluster mappings!</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":1720,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\",\"linkDestination\":\"none\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"http://localhost:8080/wp-content/uploads/2023/01/2023-01-25_21-12-49.png?w=1024\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-1720\" /></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Keeping only certain clusters</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>What if you only want to keep SOME of the existing clusters?  Let\'s try the following:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>./sizerimporter.py -fn rvtools_file.xlsx -ft rv-tools -a custom -wp \\\ncustom_clusters -pl PACS Meditech Meditech6.1</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":1723,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\",\"linkDestination\":\"none\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"http://localhost:8080/wp-content/uploads/2023/01/2023-01-25_21-22-59.png?w=1024\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-1723\" /></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Creating a workload profile based on guest operating system</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>As a final example, here we are creating a workload profile for Windows Server, another for Red Hat Enterprise, and a third for everything else:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":1725,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\",\"linkDestination\":\"none\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"http://localhost:8080/wp-content/uploads/2023/01/2023-01-25_21-47-41.png?w=1024\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-1725\" /></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Conclusion</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The great thing about this tool - </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>it\'s FAST!</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>it\'s repeatable!</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>it\'s 100% scriptable!</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>it\'s extensible!</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>This will (hopefully) make creating models for you or your customers much easier over time!  Certainly it is not what I would yet call \'feature complete\' - but I think we\'re off to a great start!</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><s>Currently the project is <a rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" href=\"https://github.com/maulepilot117/pyvmcsizer\" target=\"_blank\">hosted here on Github</a> - though we will soon move to a new home on the VMware org on Github.</s></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Update January 31, 2023</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>I am happy to report this project has been officially been published as a part of the <a rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" href=\"https://github.com/vmware-samples/vmware-cloud-sizer-companion-cli\" target=\"_blank\">VMware collection of projects on Github!</a></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Update Februyary 7, 2023</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>New release on Github:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Get results for EITHER VMC on AWS or Google Cloud VMware Engine (GCVE)</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Include all VM, or only those powered on / suspended </li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Include specific workloads by VM Name, cluster, or Guest operating system </li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Exclude specific workloads by VM Name, cluster, or Guest operating system </li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Create workload profiles based on:<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Current vm:cluster distribution ‚Äì all clusters</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Current vm:cluster distribution ‚Äì some clusters</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Guest OS based on text string filter</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>VM name based on text string filter</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list --></li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Identify VM exceptions or host incompatibilities</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Present results on-screen </li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Optionally get a PDF</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Update February 20, 2023</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>New release on Github:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>refactored to support subcommands - this will better support new functionality in the future, e.g. quick sizing, reverse sizing, ect</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>updated README and documentation / screen shots</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>fixed a couple bugs</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Update March 10, 2023</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>New release on Github:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>ability to import multiple files at once (provided same type and version)</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>ability to select preferred node type</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>ability to specify stretched vs. single AZ</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>ability to specify provisioned vs. utilized storage</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->','A CLI \'companion\' to the VMware Cloud Sizer','Introducing the VMware Cloud Sizer Companion CLI!  This is a python-based client that can be used to model workloads in VMware Cloud... quickly, easily, repeatedly, and reliably!','publish','open','open','','a-cli-companion-to-the-vmware-cloud-sizer','','','2023-01-25 21:55:34','2023-01-26 02:55:34','',0,'https://occasional-it.com/?p=1696',0,'post','',0),(1699,2,'2023-01-17 16:34:55','2023-01-17 21:34:55','','argparse_structure','','inherit','open','closed','','argparse_structure','','','2023-01-17 16:34:55','2023-01-17 21:34:55','',1696,'http://localhost:8080/wp-content/uploads/2023/01/argparse_structure.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(1700,2,'2023-01-17 16:35:57','2023-01-17 21:35:57','','pyvmcsizer','','inherit','open','closed','','pyvmcsizer','','','2023-01-17 16:35:57','2023-01-17 21:35:57','',1696,'http://localhost:8080/wp-content/uploads/2023/01/pyvmcsizer.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(1702,2,'2023-01-17 16:38:11','2023-01-17 21:38:11','','pyvmc_refactor','','inherit','open','closed','','pyvmc_refactor','','','2023-01-17 16:38:11','2023-01-17 21:38:11','',1650,'http://localhost:8080/wp-content/uploads/2023/01/pyvmc_refactor.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(1713,2,'2023-01-25 21:05:15','2023-01-26 02:05:15','','2023-01-25_21-04-43','','inherit','open','closed','','2023-01-25_21-04-43','','','2023-01-25 21:05:15','2023-01-26 02:05:15','',1696,'http://localhost:8080/wp-content/uploads/2023/01/2023-01-25_21-04-43.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(1714,2,'2023-01-25 21:05:22','2023-01-26 02:05:22','','2023-01-25_21-05-01','','inherit','open','closed','','2023-01-25_21-05-01','','','2023-01-25 21:05:22','2023-01-26 02:05:22','',1696,'http://localhost:8080/wp-content/uploads/2023/01/2023-01-25_21-05-01.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(1718,2,'2023-01-25 21:10:05','2023-01-26 02:10:05','','2023-01-25_21-09-52','','inherit','open','closed','','2023-01-25_21-09-52','','','2023-01-25 21:10:05','2023-01-26 02:10:05','',1696,'http://localhost:8080/wp-content/uploads/2023/01/2023-01-25_21-09-52.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(1720,2,'2023-01-25 21:13:08','2023-01-26 02:13:08','','2023-01-25_21-12-49','','inherit','open','closed','','2023-01-25_21-12-49','','','2023-01-25 21:13:08','2023-01-26 02:13:08','',1696,'http://localhost:8080/wp-content/uploads/2023/01/2023-01-25_21-12-49.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(1723,2,'2023-01-25 21:23:12','2023-01-26 02:23:12','','2023-01-25_21-22-59','','inherit','open','closed','','2023-01-25_21-22-59','','','2023-01-25 21:23:12','2023-01-26 02:23:12','',1696,'http://localhost:8080/wp-content/uploads/2023/01/2023-01-25_21-22-59.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(1725,2,'2023-01-25 21:48:04','2023-01-26 02:48:04','','2023-01-25_21-47-41','','inherit','open','closed','','2023-01-25_21-47-41','','','2023-01-25 21:48:04','2023-01-26 02:48:04','',1696,'http://localhost:8080/wp-content/uploads/2023/01/2023-01-25_21-47-41.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(1727,2,'2023-01-25 21:50:32','2023-01-26 02:50:32','','2023-01-25_21-50-22','','inherit','open','closed','','2023-01-25_21-50-22','','','2023-01-25 21:50:32','2023-01-26 02:50:32','',1696,'http://localhost:8080/wp-content/uploads/2023/01/2023-01-25_21-50-22.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(1728,1,'2024-03-09 11:24:23','2024-03-09 11:24:23',' ','','','publish','closed','closed','','1728','','','2024-03-09 11:24:23','2024-03-09 11:24:23','',0,'http://localhost:8080/?p=1728',13,'nav_menu_item','',0),(1729,1,'2024-03-09 11:24:23','2024-03-09 11:24:23',' ','','','publish','closed','closed','','1729','','','2024-03-09 11:24:23','2024-03-09 11:24:23','',0,'http://localhost:8080/?p=1729',7,'nav_menu_item','',0),(1730,1,'2024-03-09 11:24:23','2024-03-09 11:24:23',' ','','','publish','closed','closed','','1730','','','2024-03-09 11:24:23','2024-03-09 11:24:23','',0,'http://localhost:8080/?p=1730',8,'nav_menu_item','',0),(1755,2,'2023-03-20 08:52:25','0000-00-00 00:00:00','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>I am in the middle of a pilot for VMware Cloud Disaster Recovery and VMware Cloud on AWS... my customer is running the solution through its paces, and one of their challenges - common to many - is how to handle workloads in the \'recovery\' environment when those workloads must boot into the environment - with absolutely no changes to their network configuration.  <a rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" href=\"https://occasional-it.com/2022/12/23/using-hcx-stretched-networks-for-disaster-recovery/\" target=\"_blank\">In a previous post</a> I discussed how to leverage HCX for stretched networking... which of course can help with this issue.  However it is not for everyone - stretched layer 2 networking brings its own challenges with it, and many customers choose to leverage the available tooling withing the VMware Cloud portfolio to accomplish something similar - no changes to IP addressing - simply by duplicating network segments in the cloud. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>My current customer is leveraging the built-in capabilities of NSX-T in VMware Cloud on AWS to create all the network segments necessary for recovery on a T1 gateway configured with network address translation (NAT).  Obviously one of the most critical components of the infrastructure for a recovery environment is the ability to reliably resolve names to IP addresses.  Of course, that also means that if the recovered workloads are going to boot with no changes, that means the workload IP configuration will cause the workload to send its DNS resolution queries to a DNS system that does not / may not exist in the recovery location... so we have something of a dilemma...  How can we provide:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>DNS resolution services in the recovery location </li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>using the same DNS resolver address(es) as those in production (to accommodate the recovered workload IP configuration)</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>without corrupting / poisoning the production DNS infrastructure</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>yet keeping recovery DNS services up to date with the latest changes in the environment?</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>While it may not be a \'silver bullet,\' one possible solution is to leverage the DNS forwarding capabilities of the NSX platform.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":1760,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\",\"linkDestination\":\"none\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"http://localhost:8080/wp-content/uploads/2023/03/dns-setup.png?w=1024\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-1760\" /></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->','How to Handle DNS in DR?','','draft','open','open','','','','','2023-03-20 08:52:25','0000-00-00 00:00:00','',0,'https://occasional-it.com/?p=1755',0,'post','',0),(1760,2,'2023-03-19 19:53:27','2023-03-19 23:53:27','','dns-setup','','inherit','open','closed','','dns-setup','','','2023-03-19 19:53:27','2023-03-19 23:53:27','',1755,'http://localhost:8080/wp-content/uploads/2023/03/dns-setup.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(1768,2,'2023-05-17 09:34:02','2023-05-17 13:34:02','','pyvmc_refactor','','inherit','open','closed','','pyvmc_refactor-2','','','2023-05-17 09:34:02','2023-05-17 13:34:02','',1650,'http://localhost:8080/wp-content/uploads/2023/05/pyvmc_refactor.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(1769,2,'2023-05-17 09:34:34','2023-05-17 13:34:34','','pyvmc_refactor-1','','inherit','open','closed','','pyvmc_refactor-1','','','2023-05-17 09:34:34','2023-05-17 13:34:34','',1650,'http://localhost:8080/wp-content/uploads/2023/05/pyvmc_refactor-1.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(1772,2,'2023-09-07 21:30:08','2023-09-08 01:30:08','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>I had a customer pose a challenge to me recently... they are using VMC on AWS for DR, with Site Recovery.&nbsp; Based on the size of the recovery environment, and the number of users (3000+) that will need access to the environment during a DR exercise, they have deployed (2) SDDCs - one for the replication and recovered server workloads, and a second for the VDI instances (they are using Horizon). So one of their requirements is to ensure the desktops in the \'production\' DR pool can get access to the \'production\' DR server workloads during an actual DR event.&nbsp; They also would like to be able to test DR as well, of course, and for this purpose they have a small pool of \'test\' desktops that need to access the \'test\' server workloads during a DR test.&nbsp; For the benefit of both users and administrators, they desire a separate pool of desktops that have a different desktop background, with different colors, etc, so that users know when they are in a \'test\' environment and when they are in the \'prod\' environment.&nbsp; For obvious reasons, they also can not allow the test and prod environments to mix in any way - they do not wish to corrupt or disrupt production in any way.&nbsp; So their requirements are as follows:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4 class=\"wp-block-heading\">DR testing</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>server workloads are recovered into an isolated network environment</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>server workloads must be recovered with same IP addresses as production</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>it is assumed for failover testing production is still live, therefore it is expected networks will NOT be \'live\' in VMC, but isolated in some way</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>server workloads must have connectivity to each other</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>server workloads and networks&nbsp;<strong><em>must not</em></strong>&nbsp;be able to conflict with/disrupt / interrupt production workloads in any way</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>desktops must be available for testing recovered \'test\' servers</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>desktops must&nbsp;<strong><em>only</em></strong>&nbsp;be allowed to connect to the recovered test servers - never production</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4 class=\"wp-block-heading\">DR failover event</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>server workloads are recovered into an connected network environment</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>server workloads must be recovered with same IP addresses as production</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>it is assumed for failover production is down, therefore it is expected networks will be live in VMC</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>server workloads must have connectivity to each other</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>desktops must be available for testing recovered servers</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>desktops must&nbsp;<strong><em>only</em></strong>&nbsp;be allowed to connect to the live recovered servers - never the test environment</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Their questions revolved all around connectivity from the \'test\' desktops to the \'test\' servers, and the \'prod\' desktops to the \'prod\' recovered workloads.&nbsp; This customer chose to recreate all their production workload network segments in the cloud, rather than using HCX to stretch networks... however if they chose to use HCX to provide the connectivity services, I don\'t believe it would have changed any of the other requirements, or the solution.&nbsp; See the attached diagram for the environment they had already built.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":1774,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\",\"linkDestination\":\"none\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"http://localhost:8080/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/customer-connectivity.png?w=1024\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-1774\" /></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>After talking it through with them, and discussing it with some team members internally a bit, we came up with the following solution... grouping the two SDDCs with a SDDC Group to connect them - this will provide high-speed access for production desktops to the recovered workloads during a failover event.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>For the testing connectivity, one of two options...</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Option 1 - T1 Policy VPN</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Create a T1 policy VPN to connect the test desktops running behind their isolated T1 - see attached diagram.  </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":1776,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\",\"linkDestination\":\"none\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"http://localhost:8080/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/customer-option1.png?w=1024\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-1776\" /></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The process for building a T1 policy VPN between the two NAT T1 Gateways is found here: <a rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" href=\"https://vmc.techzone.vmware.com/understanding-vpn-customer-created-nsx-t1s-vmc-aws\" target=\"_blank\">https://vmc.techzone.vmware.com/understanding-vpn-customer-created-nsx-t1s-vmc-aws </a></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Option 2 - HCX Stretched Network</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Create a HCX stretched network between the test server segment(s) to the isolated VDI environment - see attached diagram... the important detail here is the VDI segment must be created in the server SDDC, and then stretched into the VDI SDDC.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":1777,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\",\"linkDestination\":\"none\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"http://localhost:8080/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/customer-option2.png?w=1024\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-1777\" /></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>I ran all the required connectivity tests - </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":1782,\"width\":\"770px\",\"height\":\"auto\",\"sizeSlug\":\"large\",\"linkDestination\":\"none\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large is-resized\"><img src=\"http://localhost:8080/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/2023-09-07_21-03-12.png?w=1024\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-1782\" style=\"width:770px;height:auto\" /></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Access to Horizon Desktops</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The only remaining item was how to actually connect to the Horizon instances... building off the initial diagram, it is easy enough to add the necessary Horizon infrastructure to illustrate how the connection servers and UAG servers might be added to the solution:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":1775,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\",\"linkDestination\":\"none\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"http://localhost:8080/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/customer-horizon-uag.png?w=1024\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-1775\" /></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Add some public IP addresses and NAT rules for the UAG servers, and users should be able to connect to the test desktop pool.  You could easily extend this for a second set of UAG servers for the \'production\' desktops instances.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Happy computing!</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','VMware Cloud - Desktop Connectivity Options for DR Workloads','','publish','open','open','','vmware-cloud-desktop-connectivity-options-for-dr-workloads','','','2023-09-07 21:30:08','2023-09-08 01:30:08','',0,'https://occasional-it.com/?p=1772',0,'post','',0),(1774,2,'2023-09-07 21:07:52','2023-09-08 01:07:52','','customer-connectivity','','inherit','open','closed','','customer-connectivity','','','2023-09-07 21:07:52','2023-09-08 01:07:52','',1772,'http://localhost:8080/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/customer-connectivity.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(1775,2,'2023-09-07 21:07:55','2023-09-08 01:07:55','','customer-Horizon-UAG','','inherit','open','closed','','customer-horizon-uag','','','2023-09-07 21:07:55','2023-09-08 01:07:55','',1772,'http://localhost:8080/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/customer-horizon-uag.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(1776,2,'2023-09-07 21:07:58','2023-09-08 01:07:58','','customer-option1','','inherit','open','closed','','customer-option1','','','2023-09-07 21:07:58','2023-09-08 01:07:58','',1772,'http://localhost:8080/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/customer-option1.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(1777,2,'2023-09-07 21:08:02','2023-09-08 01:08:02','','customer-option2','','inherit','open','closed','','customer-option2','','','2023-09-07 21:08:02','2023-09-08 01:08:02','',1772,'http://localhost:8080/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/customer-option2.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(1782,2,'2023-09-07 21:18:32','2023-09-08 01:18:32','','2023-09-07_21-03-12','','inherit','open','closed','','2023-09-07_21-03-12','','','2023-09-07 21:18:32','2023-09-08 01:18:32','',1772,'http://localhost:8080/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/2023-09-07_21-03-12.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(1789,2,'2023-09-09 12:05:01','0000-00-00 00:00:00','','Why you will most likely never go all native','','draft','open','open','','','','','2023-09-09 12:05:01','0000-00-00 00:00:00','',0,'http://occasional-it.com/?p=1789',0,'post','',0),(1790,2,'2022-08-31 12:34:29','2022-08-31 16:34:29','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>It\'s been a minute!  Though I haven\'t posted in recent months, I have been very busy working on new projects!  I am pleased to share here that this week I had the pleasure to present at VMware Explore 2022 alongside one of my colleagues, <a rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" href=\"https://www.linkedin.com/in/whstudio1/\" target=\"_blank\">Chris White</a>!  We presented in the Code Theater on \"Getting Started with VMware Cloud APIs\" - one of the many things I have been working on this past year.  </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":1640,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\",\"linkDestination\":\"none\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"http://localhost:8080/wp-content/uploads/2022/08/1661915688135.jpg?w=1024\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-1640\" /></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>I had a great time, and Chris is a fantastic presenter to work with!  </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>We covered the very basics of how to get started with APIs in VMware Cloud on AWS - and though our chosen language is Python (for now), working with VMware Cloud on AWS, really the approach should be applicable to any language and anything that uses an API!</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>First, I demonstrate how to authenticate to VMware\'s cloud service using a \"refresh token\" and then how to leverage the Cloud Service Portal API to add a user to a group.  Then, Chris uses the VMC API to obtain the API endpoint for the NSX Manager, and adds a network segment, builds a firewall rule, and displays the route table.  </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The audience was great - lots of questions and participation, we reference the documentation to make sure you have something to refer back to, and all the examples are online!</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>You can find all the code exmples, etc, here:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li>‚ÄãGitHub Repository of code examples<ul><li><a rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" href=\"https://github.com/maulepilot117/vmwareexplore2022\" target=\"_blank\">https://github.com/maulepilot117/vmwareexplore2022</a></li></ul></li><li>‚ÄãVMware Developer Center<ul><li><a rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" href=\"https://developer.vmware.com/\" target=\"_blank\">https://developer.vmware.com</a></li><li><a rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" href=\"https://vmc.vmware.com/console/developer\" target=\"_blank\">https://vmc.vmware.com/console/developer</a></li></ul></li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>And of course, much of this is built off our work with a couple of ‚ÄãVMware Flings:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li>Python Client for VMC on AWS<ul><li><a href=\"https://flings.vmware.com/python-client-for-vmc-on-aws\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">https://flings.vmware.com/python-client-for-vmc-on-aws</a></li></ul></li><li>SDDC Import/Export for VMware Cloud on AWS<ul><li><a href=\"https://flings.vmware.com/sddc-import-export-for-vmware-cloud-on-aws\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">https://flings.vmware.com/sddc-import-export-for-vmware-cloud-on-aws</a></li></ul></li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Finally, you can find the entire recorded session here:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:embed {\"url\":\"https://youtu.be/vZCBU_orxAM\",\"type\":\"video\",\"providerNameSlug\":\"youtube\",\"responsive\":true,\"className\":\"wp-embed-aspect-16-9 wp-has-aspect-ratio\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-embed is-type-video is-provider-youtube wp-block-embed-youtube wp-embed-aspect-16-9 wp-has-aspect-ratio\"><div class=\"wp-block-embed__wrapper\">\nhttps://youtu.be/vZCBU_orxAM\n</div></figure>\n<!-- /wp:embed -->','Back from a long hiatus','','publish','open','open','','back-from-a-long-hiatus','','','2022-08-31 12:34:29','2022-08-31 16:34:29','',0,'http://fr0gger03.wordpress.com/?p=3',0,'post','',0),(1791,2,'2021-09-13 16:32:25','2021-09-13 20:32:25','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>This one was a relatively straightforward update, but one I was happy to implement.   You can retrieve help on available commands in the <a rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" href=\"https://flings.vmware.com/python-client-for-vmc-on-aws\" target=\"_blank\">Python Client for VMware Cloud on AWS</a> by issuing one of the following commands:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>python pyVMC.py</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>... or ...</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>python pyVMC.py help</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Previously, if a user asked for help in <a rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" href=\"https://flings.vmware.com/python-client-for-vmc-on-aws\" target=\"_blank\">pyVMC</a>, they would receive a lengthy list of available commands - unsorted, unorganized, etc...  It looked like this:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>Welcome to PyVMC !\n\nHere are the currently supported commands: \n\nTo search for CSP users with a specific service role:\n	find-csp-user-by-service-role &#091;service role name]\n\nTo get a list of your VMs:\n	show-vms\n\nTo display a list of your SDDCs:\n	show-sddcs\n\nTo get a view of your selected SDDC:\n	show-sddc-state\n\nTo show the list of organization users:\n	show-org-users\n\nTo show your access token:\n	get-access-token\n\nTo show your current networks:\n	show-network\n\nTo create a new network:\n	new-network &#091;NAME] &#091;ROUTED] &#091;GATEWAY_ADDRESS] &#091;DHCP_RANGE] &#091;DOMAIN_NAME] for a DHCP network\n	new-network &#091;NAME] &#091;ROUTED] &#091;GATEWAY_ADDRESS] for a static network\n	new-network &#091;NAME] &#091;DISCONNECTED] &#091;GATEWAY_ADDRESS]  for a disconnected network\n	new-network &#091;NAME] &#091;EXTENDED] &#091;GATEWAY_ADDRESS] &#091;TUNNEL_ID] for an extended network\n\nTo remove a network:\n	remove-network\n\nAdd CSP user to a group:\n	add-users-to-csp-group &#091;GROUP_ID] &#091;EMAILS]\n\nTo show CSP groups:\n	show-csp-groups\n\nTo show CSP group members:\n	show-csp-group-members &#091;GROUP_ID]\n\nTo show CSP group diff - this compares the roles in the specified group with every user in the org and prints out a user-by-user diff:\n	show-csp-group-diff &#091;GROUP_ID] &#091;showall|skipmembers|skipowners]\n\nTo show a CSP user:\n	show-csp-org-users &#091;email]\n\nTo show CSP service roles for the currently logged in user:\n	show-csp-service-roles\n\nTo show the CGW security rules:\n	show-cgw-rule\n\nTo create a new CGW security rule\n	new-cgw-rule &#091;NAME] &#091;SOURCE-GROUPS] &#091;DESTINATION-GROUPS] &#091;SERVICE] &#091;ACTION] &#091;SCOPE] &#091;SEQUENCE-NUMBER]\n\nTo delete a CGW security rule:\n	remove-cgw-rule &#091;RULE_ID]\n\nTo show the MGW security rules:\n	show-mgw-rule\n\nTo create a new MGW security rule\n	new-mgw-rule &#091;NAME] &#091;SOURCE-GROUPS] &#091;DESTINATION-GROUPS] &#091;SERVICE] &#091;ACTION] &#091;SEQUENCE-NUMBER]\n\nTo delete a MGW security rule:\n	remove-mgw-rule &#091;RULE_ID]\n\nTo show the DFW sections:\n	show-dfw-section\n\nTo create a new DFW section\n	new-dfw-section &#091;NAME]&#091;CATEGORY]\n\nTo delete a DFW section:\n	remove-dfw-section &#091;RULE_ID]\n\nTo show the DFW security rules within a section\n	show-dfw-section-rules &#091;SECTION]\n\nTo create a new DFW security rule\n	new-dfw-rule &#091;NAME] &#091;SOURCE-GROUPS] &#091;DESTINATION-GROUPS] &#091;SERVICE] &#091;ACTION] &#091;SECTION] &#091;SEQUENCE-NUMBER]\n\nTo delete a DFW rule:\n	remove-dfw-rule &#091;SECTION_ID]&#091;RULE_ID]\n\n...</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>Updated Help Section</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Now, however, the help menu returns an alphabetized, grouped listing as follows:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>Welcome to PyVMC !\n\nHere are the currently supported commands: \n\nAWS Account and VPC\n	set-sddc-connected-services: change whether to use S3 over the Internet or via the ENI\n	show-compatible-subnets &#091;LINKEDACCOUNTID] &#091;REGION]: show compatible native AWS subnets connected to the SDDC\n	show-connected-accounts: show native AWS accounts connected to the SDDC\n	show-sddc-connected-vpc: show the VPC connected to the SDDC\n	show-shadow-account: show the Shadow AWS Account VMC is deployed in\n\nBGP and Networking\n	new-t0-prefix-list: create a new T0 BGP Prefix List\n	remove-t0-prefix-list &#091;PREFIX LIST ID]: you can see current prefix list with \'show-t0-prefix-lists\': remove a T0 BGP Prefix List\n	set-bgp-as &#091;ASN]: update the BGP AS number\n	set-mtu: set the MTU configured over the Direct Connect\n	show-mtu: show the MTU configured over the Direct Connect\n	show-egress-interface-counters: show current Internet interface egress counters\n	show-sddc-bgp-as: show the BGP AS number\n	show-sddc-bgp-vpn: show whether DX is preferred over VPN\n	show-t0-bgp-neighbors: show T0 BGP neighbors\n	show-t0-prefix-lists: show T0 prefix lists\n	show-t0-routes: show routes at the T0 router\n\nDNS \n	show-dns-services: show DNS services\n	show-dns-zones: show DNS zones\n\nInventory Groups\n	new-group &#091;CGW/MGW] &#091;Group_ID]: create a new group\n	remove-group &#091;CGW/MGW]&#091;Group_ID]: remove a group\n	show-group &#091;CGW/MGW] &#091;Group_ID]: show existing groups\n	show-group-association &#091;CGW/MGW] &#091;Group_ID]: show security rules used by a groups\n\nFirewall - Distributed\n	new-dfw-rule &#091;NAME] &#091;SOURCE-GROUPS] &#091;DESTINATION-GROUPS] &#091;SERVICE] &#091;ACTION] &#091;SECTION] &#091;SEQUENCE-NUMBER]: create a new DFW security rule\n	new-dfw-section &#091;NAME]&#091;CATEGORY]: create a new DFW section\n	remove-dfw-rule &#091;SECTION_ID]&#091;RULE_ID]: delete a DFW rule\n	remove-dfw-section &#091;RULE_ID]: delete a DFW section\n	show-dfw-section: show the DFW sections\n	show-dfw-section-rules &#091;SECTION]: show the DFW security rules within a section\n\nFirewall - T0\n	new-cgw-rule &#091;NAME] &#091;SOURCE-GROUPS] &#091;DESTINATION-GROUPS] &#091;SERVICE] &#091;ACTION] &#091;SCOPE] &#091;SEQUENCE-NUMBER]: create a new CGW security rule\n	new-mgw-rule &#091;NAME] &#091;SOURCE-GROUPS] &#091;DESTINATION-GROUPS] &#091;SERVICE] &#091;ACTION] &#091;SEQUENCE-NUMBER]: create a new MGW security rule\n	remove-cgw-rule &#091;RULE_ID]: delete a CGW security rule\n	remove-mgw-rule &#091;RULE_ID]: delete a MGW security rule\n	show-cgw-rule: show the CGW security rules\n	show-mgw-rule: show the MGW security rules\n\nFirewall Services\n	new-service: create a new service\n	remove-service &#091;SERVICE-ID]: remove a service\n	show-services &#091;SERVICE-ID]: show a specific service\n	show-services: show services\n\nNAT\n	new-nat-rule: To create a new NAT rule\n	remove-nat-rule: remove a NAT rule\n	show-nat: show the configured NAT rules\n	show-nat &#091;NAT-RULE-ID] for statistics of a rule: show the statistics for a specific NAT rule\n\nPublic IP addressing\n	new-sddc-public-ip: request a new public IP\n	remove-sddc-public-ip: remove an existing public IP\n	set-sddc-public-ip: update the description of an existing public IP\n	show-sddc-public-ip: show the public IPs\n\nSDDC\n	get-access-token: show your access token\n	show-sddc-state: get a view of your selected SDDC\n	show-sddcs: display a lit of your SDDCs\n	show-vms: get a list of your VMs\n\nUser and Group management\n	add-users-to-csp-group &#091;GROUP_ID] &#091;EMAILS]: CSP user to a group\n	show-csp-group-diff &#091;GROUP_ID] &#091;showall|skipmembers|skipowners]: this compares the roles in the specified group with every user in the org and prints out a user-by-user diff\n	show-csp-group-members &#091;GROUP_ID]: show CSP group members\n	show-csp-groups: To show CSP groups\n	show-csp-org-users &#091;email]: show a CSP user\n	show-csp-service-roles: show CSP service roles for the currently logged in user\n	find-csp-user-by-service-role &#091;service role name]: search for CSP users with a specific service role\n	show-org-users: show the list of organization users\n\nVirtual Machine Networking\n	show-network: show your current networks\n	new-network &#091;NAME] &#091;DISCONNECTED] &#091;GATEWAY_ADDRESS]  for a disconnected network\n	new-network &#091;NAME] &#091;EXTENDED] &#091;GATEWAY_ADDRESS] &#091;TUNNEL_ID] for an extended network\n	new-network &#091;NAME] &#091;ROUTED] &#091;GATEWAY_ADDRESS] &#091;DHCP_RANGE] &#091;DOMAIN_NAME] for a DHCP network\n	new-network &#091;NAME] &#091;ROUTED] &#091;GATEWAY_ADDRESS] for a static network\n	remove-network: remove a network\n\nVPN\n	new-l2vpn &#091;NAME] &#091;LOCAL_ENDPOINT] &#091;REMOTE_PEER]: create a new L2VPN\n	remove-l2VPN &#091;ID]: remove a L2VPN\n	remove-vpn &#091;VPN-ID]: remove a VPN\n	remove-vpn-ike-profile &#091;ID]: remove a VPN IKE profile\n	remove-vpn-ipsec-tunnel-profile &#091;ID]: To remove a VPN IPSec Tunnel profile\n	show-l2vpn: show l2 vpn\n	show-l2vpn-services: show l2 vpn services\n	show-vpn: show the configured VPN\n	show-vpn &#091;VPN_ID]: show the VPN statistics\n	show-vpn-ike-profile: show the VPN IKE profiles\n	show-vpn-internet-ip: show the public IP used for VPN services\n	show-vpn-ipsec-tunnel-profile: show the VPN tunnel profile\n	show-vpn-ipsec-endpoints: show the VPN IPSec endpoints\n</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>it\'s a little change, but one I think that makes using the tool much easier!</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Enjoy!</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Update to pyVMC - new Help section!','Quick update to the Help section to make it easier and more concise for users!','publish','open','open','','update-to-pyvmc-new-help-section','','','2021-09-13 16:32:25','2021-09-13 20:32:25','',0,'https://occasional-it.com/?p=1550',0,'post','',0),(1792,2,'2023-10-29 09:25:08','2023-10-29 13:25:08','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>I have experienced several inflection points in my career.  The first was during my time as a Microsoft Certified Instructor during the 1990\'s...  I learned about Citrix for the first time - at the time their product was called Winframe.  I was astounded by the idea (and the experience) of hosting a complete, immersive desktop on a single Windows instance for dozens of users... it was a game changer!</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The second was in 1999 - I was working for a reseller in California, and my job for the week was to install Citrix Metaframe on a bunch of Windows servers at Peoplesoft in Pleasanton, CA so they could host their applications for users remotely.  One of the other consultants working on the project was running a linux laptop, and yet I saw a window running on his laptop that clearly had an instance of Windows 98 running... \"What is that!?!\" I asked - and he told me about this cool tool called VMware Workstation.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Those two incidents together have shaped my career for the past 25 years.  I went on to work for Citrix for a few years as a presales engineer.  In 2004, VMware came along and hired away most of the team I was working with, and though they didn\'t have an opening for someone in my location then, I eventually landed a job with them in 2007.  I have been with them since.  Even my time as a vSpecialist for EMC - while technically not a VMware employee - was spent working on VMware topics and technology.  I have been a Systems engineer for the core sales team in Virginia and the mid-atlantic, a business strategy solution architect, a vSAN Systems Engineer, and most recently a Cloud Solutions Architect.  I have worked with customers large and small - across multiple verticals, including Capital One, Fedex, Bank of America, the State of VA, Northwell Health, Health New England, Cleveland Clinic, various state and federal agencies, and numerous cities and counties.  Nearly every post on my occasional blog is taken directly from my personal experience working with customers - I write to help crystallize my thoughts and solidify my knowledge... if any of this has been helpful to my colleagues and customers, so much the better. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>VMware is a special company and has been my home for the better part of the past 20 years.  No matter what happens next I have enjoyed my time with my company and my customers.   We have literally changed the industry... the way technology has been built and sold has fundamentally changed due to VMware - servers don\'t or function look the same, storage arrays don\'t look or function the same, networking equipment doesn‚Äôt look or function the same.  I recall at one company meeting Diane Greene talking to us all and pointing out - \"We have a chance to insert an entirely new layer into the technology stack in the datacenter...\"  And we did it - We have altered the datacenter industry forever. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>This week represents another major inflection point as Broadcom finalizes and closes its acquisition of VMware.  I will be staying with Broadcom post-acquisition for the foreseeable future, but I have no idea what the gig is going to be like.  I don\'t know what the next weeks and years will bring - but it is clear that it won\'t be the same - both from Broadcom\'s past acquisitions, as well as from how this one has proceeded.  </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>I will be taking an extended hiatus from blogging until my path is clear (who am i kidding?  I only write a few articles a year anyways)- so until then...</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>So long and thanks for all the fish.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Inflection points...','','publish','open','open','','inflection-points','','','2024-03-09 11:25:11','2024-03-09 11:25:11','',0,'https://occasional-it.com/?p=1790',0,'post','',0),(1793,1,'2024-03-09 11:25:01','2024-03-09 11:25:01','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Welcome to WordPress. This is your first post. Edit or delete it, then start writing!</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Hello world!','','inherit','closed','closed','','1-revision-v1','','','2024-03-09 11:25:01','2024-03-09 11:25:01','',1,'http://localhost:8080/?p=1793',0,'revision','',0),(1794,1,'2024-03-09 11:25:05','2024-03-09 11:25:05','{\"version\": 2, \"isGlobalStylesUserThemeJSON\": true }','Custom Styles','','publish','closed','closed','','wp-global-styles-twentytwentyfour','','','2024-03-09 11:25:05','2024-03-09 11:25:05','',0,'http://localhost:8080/?p=1794',0,'wp_global_styles','',0),(1795,1,'2024-03-09 11:25:11','2024-03-09 11:25:11','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>I have experienced several inflection points in my career.  The first was during my time as a Microsoft Certified Instructor during the 1990\'s...  I learned about Citrix for the first time - at the time their product was called Winframe.  I was astounded by the idea (and the experience) of hosting a complete, immersive desktop on a single Windows instance for dozens of users... it was a game changer!</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The second was in 1999 - I was working for a reseller in California, and my job for the week was to install Citrix Metaframe on a b